src:
Turks transferred 10 billion lira ($ 889 million) worth of forex deposits into a new instrument the government introduced this week that covers any FX depreciation losses, Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said on Thursday.

Since the instrument was announced on Monday the lira has rallied sharply from an all-time low, raising questions over whether the central bank is backing state-bank interventions to sell dollars and accelerate the gains.

"Now people are asking why we intervened through the central bank or Treasury," Nebati said on broadcaster NTV. "Is Turkey an unskillful country that watches the developments by itself and doesn't use all the instruments at its disposal in a positive way? It uses all the instruments," he added.
tgt:
Turks transferred 10 billion lira ($ 889 million) worth of forex deposits into a new instrument the government introduced this week that covers any FX depreciation losses, Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said on Thursday.

The lira has rallied sharply from an all-time low since the instrument was announced on Monday, raising questions over whether the central bank was backing state-bank interventions to sell dollars and accelerate the gains.

"Now people are asking why we intervened through the central bank or Treasury," broadcaster NTV quoted Nebati as saying. "Is Turkey an unskillful country that monitors the developments by itself and doesn't use all the instruments at its disposal in a positive way? It uses all the instruments at its disposal," he added.
title: c5bcbc0f05e29b74360fe9b2495c4166

src:
The Council of Europe said on Friday it ruled to notify Turkey of its intention to launch "infringement proceedings" against the country over its failure to release philanthropist Osman Kavala in line with a European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) ruling.

The Council asked Ankara to submit its view on the case by Jan 19, 2022, the statement said.

Last week a Turkish court ruled to keep Kavala in prison, extending his four-year detention without conviction in a trial which has added to strains in Ankara's troubled relations with its Western allies.
tgt:
The Council of Europe said on Friday it ruled it had notified Turkey of its intention to launch "infringement proceedings" against the country over its failure to release philanthropist Osman Kavala, in line with a European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) ruling.

The Council said in a statement that it had asked Ankara to submit its view on the case by the Jan 19, 2022.

A Turkish court last week ruled to keep Kavala in prison, extending his four-year detention without conviction in a trial, adding to strains in Ankara's troubled relations with its Western allies.
title: 6d41480662b856401581a57d45a8bad6

Mexico on Monday registered 429 additional fatalities due to the coronavirus, bringing the total in the country to 180,536 deaths.

According to health ministry data, Mexico also registered 2,252 new confirmed cases of coronavirus infection, for a total of 2,043,632 cases.

Mexico on Monday registered 429 additional fatalities due to the coronavirus, bringing the overall number of fatalities in the country to 180,536.

Mexico also registered 2,252 new confirmed cases of coronavirus infection for a total of 2,043,632 cases, health ministry data showed.

U.S. crude and distillate stocks fell last week while gasoline inventories rose, according to market sources citing American Petroleum Institute figures on Tuesday.

Turkish Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati on Tuesday said legal proceedings against speculative market comments made on social media had been initiated after recent currency volatility.

Nebati also told state broadcaster TRT Haber in an interview that the government remains committed to single-digit inflation, high growth, and a current account surplus.

src:
Turkey will host a major summit on Afghanistan's peace process in Istanbul from April 24 to May 4, its foreign ministry said on Tuesday, adding representatives from the Taliban and Afghan government would both attend the talks.

The meeting includes the United Nations and Qatar as part of a U.S.-backed push to jump-start the peace process. On Monday, the Taliban said it was unwilling, based on timing, to attend talks in Turkey that were initially scheduled for April 16.

"Participation in the Conference and its agenda have been the subject of extensive consultations with the Afghan parties," the ministry said. The meeting is meant to determine a roadmap for a future political settlement and end to the conflict, it added.
tgt:
Turkey plans to host a major summit on Afghanistan's peace process in Istanbul from April 24 to May 4, its foreign ministry said on Tuesday, adding representatives from the Taliban and Afghan government would both take part in the talks.

The meeting includes the United Nations and Qatar as part of a U.S.-backed push to kick-start the peace process. The Taliban said on Monday it was unwilling – based on timing – to attend talks in Turkey, initially scheduled for April 16.

"Participation in the Conference and its agenda have been the subject of extensive consultations with the Afghan parties," said the ministry in a statement. It added that the meeting was aimed at determining a roadmap for a future political settlement and ending the conflict.
title: a70a05792e161510eac75f0d2f2e8e66

Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan announced tighter measures against the coronavirus on Monday, citing the rising number of high-risk cities across the country.

Erdogan said a full weekend lockdown was to be in place during the month of Ramadan, and restaurants would only serve as delivery and take-out. A curfew that is implemented between 9 pm and 5 am across the country was continued, Erdogan said.

src:
Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it would carry out lira-settled foreign exchange forward sales, with the aim of helping exporting and importing companies to manage forex rate risk, via auctions and the derivatives market.

The lira-settled foreign exchange forward selling auctions will be held with maturities of 1 month and 3 months, the bank said. Importing and exporting companies will be able to convey their buying demands via banks, it said.
tgt:
Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it would carry out lira-settled foreign exchange forward sales, with the aim of helping exporters and importers to manage forex rate risk, via auctions and the derivatives market.

The bank said the lira-settled foreign exchange forward selling auctions would be held with maturities of 1 month and 3 months. It will allow importing and exporting companies to convey their buying demands via banks.
title: 95b6b43419e032978b3407d3bec65ca5

The Turkish central bank told banks on Monday it would provide support for forex-protected lira deposits by not applying required reserve ratios on these accounts, a document seen by Reuters said.

The central bank also told private and public banks it would pay 14 % remuneration for 16 % of forex protected Turkish lira deposits, the document showed.
tgt:
The Turkish central bank on Monday told banks it would provide support for forex-protected lira deposits by not applying required reserve ratios on such accounts, a document seen by Reuters showed.

The central bank also said it would pay 14 % remuneration for 16 % of forex-protected Turkish lira deposits to private and public banks, the document showed.

src:
Turkey's new finance minister said on Thursday the government adopted its new economic model as a "slap-like response" to those calling for interest rate hikes, after an aggressive monetary easing cycle in recent months set off a lira crash.

Nureddin Nebati, appointed early this month, said the foreign exchange rate is losing its "foam" after the government introduced a deposit-protection plan on Monday that sparked a sharp lira rebound.

"The foam started to fade away but there is more of it left," he said on broadcaster NTV, suggesting that Turkey's currency could rally further against the dollar.
tgt:
Turkey's new finance minister said on Thursday the government adopted its new economic model as a "slap-like response" to those calling for interest rate hikes, following an aggressive monetary easing cycle in recent months that set off a lira crash.

Nureddin Nebati, appointed early this month, said the foreign exchange rate is losing its "foam" after the government unveiled a deposit-protection plan on Monday that sparked a sharp lira rebound.

"The foam started to fade away but there is more of it left," he told broadcaster NTV, suggesting that Turkey's currency could rally further against the dollar.
title: 476ceb0a72edddeb6fbf741df0b68cf0

Turks transferred 10 billion lira ($ 889 million) worth of forex deposits into a new instrument the government introduced this week that covers any FX depreciation losses, Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said on Thursday.

Since the instrument was announced on Monday the lira has rallied sharply from an all-time low, raising questions over whether the central bank is backing state-bank interventions to sell dollars and accelerate the gains.

"Now people are asking why we intervened through the central bank or Treasury," Nebati said on broadcaster NTV. "Is Turkey an unskillful country that watches the developments by itself and doesn't use all the instruments at its disposal in a positive way? It uses all the instruments," he added.
tgt:
Turks transferred 10 billion lira ($ 889 million) worth of forex deposits, Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said on Thursday, into a new instrument the government introduced this week covering any FX depreciation losses.

The lira has rallied sharply from all-time lows since the instrument was announced on Monday, raising questions over whether the central bank is backing state-bank interventions to sell dollars, accelerating the gains.

"Now people are asking why we intervened through the central bank or Treasury," Nebati, speaking on broadcaster NTV, said. "Is Turkey an unskillful country that watches the developments by itself and doesn't use all the instruments at its disposal in a positive way? It uses all the instruments," he said.
title: 2bd80646a38734fee326d39cf2fc395e

src:
Turkey's Gama Enerji has reached a restructuring deal for a $ 595 million loan that it took to set up a combined cycle power plant, the company said in a statement.

Turkish lenders Is Bank, Yapi Kredi, Garanti, TSKB and Deniz were leading banks in the deal, Gama said.

Turkey's Gama Holding owns 50 % of Gama Enerji, while Malaysian electricity infrastructure firm Tenega owns 30 %, the IFC owns 14.5 % and IFC Global Infrastructure Fund Holding owns 5 %.
tgt:
Turkey's Gama Enerji has reached a restructuring deal for a $ 595 million loan that it took to establish a combined cycle power plant, the company said in a statement.

Leading banks in the deal were Turkish lenders Is Bank, Zy, Garanti, TSKB and Deniz, Gama said.

Turkey's Gama Holding owns 50 % of Gama Enerji, Malaysian electricity infrastructure firm Tenega owns 30 %, the IFC owns 14.5 %, and IFC Global Infrastructure Fund Holding owns 5 %.

src:
Canada, acting with the United States and Britain, is imposing sanctions on four Myanmar entities in response to the "military's ongoing repression" in the Asian country, the foreign ministry said in a statement on Friday.

Ottawa will not hesitate to take further measures if need be, the statement said. The sanctions target military entities responsible for supporting Myanmar's armed forces, which seized power in February this year.
tgt:
Canada, acting with the United States and Britain, is imposing sanctions on four Myanmar entities, the foreign ministry said in a statement on Friday, in retaliation for the "military's ongoing repression" in the Asian country.

Ottawa, if need be, will not hesitate to take further measures, the statement added. The sanctions target military entities responsible for backing Myanmar's armed forces after seizing power in February this year.
title: 741f0a3d7c64f4df7e764fcf87220c61

src:
Turkish central government's budget deficit stood at 17.41 billion lira ($ 1.74 billion) in October, data from the Treasury and Finance Ministry showed on Monday, with a primary deficit of 3.11 billion lira.

The budget recorded a 10-month cumulative deficit of 78.5 billion lira and a cumulative primary surplus of 78.07 billion lira.
tgt:
Turkish central government budget deficit stood at 17.41 billion lira ($ 1.74 billion) in October, data from the Treasury and Finance Ministry showed on Monday, with the primary deficit at 3.11 billion lira.

The budget recorded a 10-month cumulative deficit of 78.5 billion lira, while a cumulative primary surplus was at 78.07 billion lira.
title: 80c8b24e8517c6549b72be3ba4b57e19

Turkish central government's budget deficit stood at 17.41 billion lira ($ 1.74 billion) in October, data from the Treasury and Finance Ministry showed on Monday, with a primary deficit of 3.11 billion lira.

The budget recorded a 10-month cumulative deficit of 78.5 billion lira and a cumulative primary surplus of 78.07 billion lira.
tgt:
Turkish central government budget deficit stood at 17.41 billion lira ($ 1.74 billion) in October, data from the Treasury and Finance Ministry showed on Monday, with the primary deficit at 3.11 billion lira.

The budget recorded a 10-month cumulative deficit of 78.5 billion lira, while a cumulative primary surplus was at 78.07 billion lira.

src:
Turkey's Gama Enerji has reached a restructuring deal for a $ 595 million loan that it took to set up a combined cycle power plant, the company said in a statement.

Turkish lenders Is Bank, Yapi Kredi, Garanti, TSKB and Deniz were leading banks in the deal, Gama said.

Turkey's Gama Holding owns 50 % of Gama Enerji, while Malaysian electricity infrastructure firm Tenega owns 30 %, the IFC owns 14.5 % and IFC Global Infrastructure Fund Holding owns 5 %.
tgt:
Turkey's Gama Enerji has reached a restructuring deal for a $ 595 million loan the company took to set up a combined cycle power plant, it said in a statement.

Leading banks in the deal was Turkish lender Is Bank, Yapi Kredi, Garanti, TSKB and Deniz, Gama said.

Turkey's Gama Holding owns 50 % of Gama Enerji while Malaysian electricity infrastructure firm Tenega owns 30 %, the IFC holds 14.5 % and IFC Global Infrastructure Fund Holding holds 5 %.

src:
Turkey further eased measures meant to curb coronavirus infections on Monday including partially lifting a weekend lockdown and opening restaurants to a limited number of guests.

President Tayyip Erdogan said the lighter measures, in response to falling cases, would go into effect Tuesday. Under the new rules, nationwide daily curfews are delayed by an hour to 10 p.m.
tgt:
Turkey further eased measures aimed at curbing coronavirus infections on Monday including partly lifting a weekend lockdown and opening restaurants to a limited number of guests.

President Tayyip Erdogan said the lighter measures – in response to falling cases – would go into effect Tuesday. Nationwide daily curfews are delayed by one hour to 10 p.m. under the new rules.

src:
President Tayyip Erdogan said on Friday that Turks should keep all their savings in lira and that recent exchange rate volatility was largely under control after the lira weakened sharply in the last two months.

In a speech in Istanbul, Erdogan also called on Turks to bring their gold savings into the banking system and reiterated his unorthodox view that interest rates were the cause of inflation.
tgt:
Turks should retain all their savings in lira, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Friday, adding that recent exchange rate volatility was largely under control after the lira weakened sharply over the last two months.

Erdogan reiterated in a speech in Istanbul his unorthodox view that interest rates were the cause of inflation and also called on Turks to bring their gold savings into the banking system.

src:
Turkey's new finance minister said on Thursday the government adopted its new economic model as a "slap-like response" to those calling for interest rate hikes, after an aggressive monetary easing cycle in recent months set off a lira crash.

Nureddin Nebati, appointed early this month, said the foreign exchange rate is losing its "foam" after the government introduced a deposit-protection plan on Monday that sparked a sharp lira rebound.

"The foam started to fade away but there is more of it left," he said on broadcaster NTV, suggesting that Turkey's currency could rally further against the dollar.
tgt:
Turkey's new finance minister said on Thursday the government adopted its new economic model as a "slap-like response" to those calling for interest rate hikes following an aggressive monetary easing cycle in recent months, setting off a lira crash.

Nureddin Nebati, appointed early this month, said the forex rate is losing its "foam" after the government introduced a deposit-protection plan on Monday that sparked a sharp lira rebound.

"The foam started to fade away but there is more of it left," he told broadcaster NTV, suggesting that Turkey's currency could rally further against the dollar.
title: 50bcf463f259812a3554796190da8055

src:
President Tayyip Erdogan said on Wednesday that Turkey thwarted the speculative financial games from foreign and domestic forces, after the lira rebounded aggressively from record lows in volatile trade this week.

Speaking to his AK Party lawmakers, Erdogan said a scheme he announced on Monday to protect lira deposits succeeded in reaching this goal.

The president also repeated he will not let Turks be crushed under interest rates and inflation, and Turkey will emerge victorious from this economic battle.
tgt:
Turkey thwarted the speculative financial games from foreign and domestic forces, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Wednesday, after volatile trade this week saw the lira rebound aggressively from record lows.

Speaking to lawmakers from his AK Party, Erdogan said a scheme he announced on Monday to protect lira deposits had succeeded in reaching this goal.

The president also repeated he will not let Turks be crushed under interest rates and inflation, and said Turkey would emerge victorious from this economic battle.
title: 8fd58d5bf1df523870ccd1cb1d708791

Mexico on Sunday registered 310 additional fatalities due to the novel coronavirus, bringing the total in the country to 180,107 deaths.

According to health ministry data, Mexico also registered 3,104 new confirmed cases of coronavirus infections, for a total of 2,041,380 cases.
tgt:
Mexico on Sunday registered 310 additional fatalities due to the novel coronavirus in the country, bringing its total to 180,107 fatalities.

Mexico also registered 3,104 new confirmed cases of coronavirus infections, for total cases of 2,041,380, according to health ministry data.

src:
Turkey will lift weekend lockdowns in low and medium-risk cities and limit the restrictions to just Sundays in high and very high-risk cities as it starts a "controlled normalisation" of coronavirus measures, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Monday.

Turkey's biggest city, Istanbul, was categorised as high risk, while the capital Ankara was in the medium-risk category.

Erdogan said the list of measures would be updated every two weeks on a province-by-province basis.
tgt:
Turkey will lift weekend lockdowns in low and medium-risk cities and limit the restrictions to just Sundays in high and very high-risk cities, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Monday news agency.

Turkey's biggest city Istanbul was categorised as high risk and its capital Ankara as medium-risk category.

The list of measures will be updated on a province-by-province basis each two weeks, Erdogan said.
title: 4d9d6473c9b0bf7a761c547fc14039a2

U.S. crude and distillate stocks fell last week while gasoline inventories rose, according to market sources citing American Petroleum Institute figures on Tuesday.

Crude stocks fell by 815,000 barrels for the week ended Dec. 10. Gasoline inventories rose by 426,000 barrels and distillate stocks fell by 1 million barrels, the data showed, according to the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
tgt:
U.S. crude and distillate stocks fell last week, while gasoline stocks rose, market sources said on Tuesday citing American Petroleum Institute figures.

For the week ended Dec. 10, crude stocks were down 815,000 barrels. Gasoline inventories rose by 426,000 barrels, while distillate stocks fell by 1 million barrels, the data showed, the sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity.

src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan called on Turks to convert their foreign exchange and gold holdings through financial institutions as a "win-win" strategy for the country and themselves, after an overhaul of the central bank sent the lira down nearly 12 % in a week.

Erdogan's replacement of former governor Naci Agbal with Sahap Kavcioglu, who supports the president's view that high interest rates lead to high inflation, led to market turmoil amid concerns Turkey may return to unorthodox economic policies, including imposing capital controls to protect its currency.

src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan's nationalist ally on Thursday welcomed a case by a top prosecutor demanding the closure of the pro-Kurdish opposition, saying the party should be shut, "never to be opened again".

A Turkish prosecutor filed a case with the constitutional court on Wednesday demanding a ban on the Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) over alleged ties to Kurdish militants, the culmination of a years-long crackdown against parliament's third largest party.

Devlet Bahceli, leader of the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) which led calls for the HDP's closure in recent weeks, said it was a "criminal organisation disguised in a political cloak".
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan's nationalist ally on Thursday welcomed a case by a top prosecutor demanding closure of the pro-Kurdish opposition, saying the party should be shut "never to be opened again".

A Turkish prosecutor filed a case with the constitutional court on Wednesday demanding a ban on the Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) over alleged ties to Kurdish militants, the culmination of a years-long crackdown against parliament's third largest party.

Devlet Bahceli, leader of the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) which led calls for the HDP to be closed in recent weeks, called it a "criminal organisation disguised in a political cloak".

Turkey's Gama Holding owns 50 % of Gama Enerji, while Malaysian electricity infrastructure firm Tenega owns 30 %, the IFC owns 14.5 % and IFC Global Infrastructure Fund Holding owns 5 %.

src:
Turkey's central will monitor risks related to the foreign exchange market and do what is necessary to ensure it runs smoothly, it said in a policy framework report published on Wednesday.

"To ensure that the FX market operates efficiently, the (bank) will closely monitor exchange rate developments and related risk factors and continue to take the necessary measures and employ due instruments," it said in its annual policy report for 2022.

The bank will use reserve requirements to support its pursuit of price and financial stability objectives, it said, adding that negotiations to sign swap agreements with other central banks would continue.
tgt:
Turkey's central will monitor risks related to the forex market and do what is needed to ensure the lira runs smoothly, it said in a policy framework report published on Wednesday.

"To ensure that the FX market operates efficiently, the (bank) will closely monitor exchange rate developments and related risk factors and continue to take the necessary measures and employ due instruments," the bank said in its Annual Policy Report for 2022.

Negotiations to sign swap agreements with other central banks will continue, it said, adding that reserve requirements will be used to support its pursuit of price and financial stability objectives.
title: 579abca7ddf4609ad97d711e4981724e

src:
Goldman Sachs expects Turkish inflation to rise to 18 % in April and dip to only 15 % by year end after the ousting of the central bank governor sparked a lira selloff this month, the Wall Street bank said on Tuesday as part of several forecast revisions.

Goldman, which previously saw 12.5 % end-2021 inflation, said the central bank under new chief Sahap Kavcioglu will not be able to cut interest rates until the fourth quarter given the 13 % lira depreciation since he was appointed on March 20.

It also cut its 2021 economic growth forecast for Turkey to 3.5 % from 5.5 % before the overhaul, and also lowered its current account deficit prediction to 1.5 % of GDP from 3.5 %.

"The main risk to our forecasts is that the authorities may push for growth with premature rate cuts or an increase in lending," Goldman said in a client note.
tgt:
Goldman Sachs expects Turkish inflation to rise to 18 % in April and dip to just 15 % by year-end after the ousting of the central bank governor sparked a lira selloff this month, the Wall Street bank said on Tuesday as part of several forecast revisions.

Goldman, which previously saw 12.5 % end-2021 inflation, said the central bank under new chief Sahap Kavcioglu will be unable to cut interest rates until the fourth quarter, given the 13 % lira depreciation since he was appointed on March 20.

It also cut its 2021 economic growth forecast for Turkey to 3.5 % from 5.5 % prior to the overhaul and lowered its current account deficit prediction to 1.5 % of gross domestic product (GDP) from 3.5 %.

"The main risk to our forecasts is that the authorities may push for growth with premature rate cuts or an increase in lending," Goldman said in a client note.

src:
Turkey recorded 49,584 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Tuesday, the highest level since the start of the pandemic.

Last week President Tayyip Erdogan announced a tightening of coronavirus restrictions, including the return of full nationwide weekend lockdowns during the Islamic fasting month of Ramadan, which starts on April 13.

The latest daily death toll was 211, the highest since early January, bringing the cumulative toll to 32,667.

src:
President Tayyip Erdogan said on Wednesday that Turkey thwarted the speculative financial games from foreign and domestic forces, after the lira rebounded aggressively from record lows in volatile trade this week.

Speaking to his AK Party lawmakers, Erdogan said a scheme he announced on Monday to protect lira deposits succeeded in reaching this goal.

src:
Turkey recorded 59,187 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Tuesday, registering the highest daily rise since the beginning of the pandemic.

The total number of cases stood at 3.962 million.

The data also showed 273 people had lost their lives due to COVID-19 in the same period, bringing the total death toll to 34,455.

Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions and a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan to curb surging coronavirus infections.
tgt:
Turkey recorded 59,187 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data on Tuesday showed, registering the highest daily rise since the beginning of the pandemic.

The total cases stood at 3.962 million, the data showed.

The data also showed 273 people had died due to complications from COVID-19 during the same period, bringing the total death toll up to 34,455.

Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions, including a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic fasting month of Ramadan, to curb surging coronavirus infections.

The Turkish central bank told banks on Monday it would provide support for forex-protected lira deposits by not applying required reserve ratios on these accounts, a document seen by Reuters said.

The central bank also told private and public banks it would pay 14 % remuneration for 16 % of forex protected Turkish lira deposits, the document showed.
tgt:
The Turkish central bank informed banks on Monday it would provide support for forex-protected lira deposits by not applying required reserve ratios on these accounts, a document seen by Reuters showed.

The central bank also told private and public banks that it would pay 14 % remuneration for 16 % of forex-protected Turkish lira deposits, the document showed.

Turkish Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said on Tuesday legal proceedings were initiated against speculative market comments made on social media following recent currency volatility.

src:
Turkey and Germany agree that all foreign mercenaries in Libya need to leave the country, but Ankara has a bilateral agreement with the Libyan government for its troops to be stationed there, Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Thursday.

On Wednesday, German Chancellor Angela Merkel told Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan that the withdrawal of foreign troops from Libya would be an "important signal" as both leaders vowed to support the new interim government, a German government spokesman said.

Speaking at a news conference with his German counterpart Heiko Maas in Berlin, Cavusoglu said Turkish troops in Libya were there under agreement with Libya's previous Government of National Accord and should not be confused with the foreign mercenaries stationed there.
tgt:
Turkey and Germany agree that all foreign mercenaries in Libya need to leave the country, Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Thursday, but Ankara has a bilateral agreement with the Libyan government for its troops to be stationed there.

German Chancellor Angela Merkel told Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Wednesday that the withdrawal of foreign troops from Libya would be an "important signal", a German government spokesman said, as both leaders vowed to support the new interim government.

Speaking at a joint news conference with his German counterpart Heiko Maas in Berlin, Cavusoglu said Turkish troops in Libya were there under agreement with Libya's previous Government of National Accord, and should not be confused with the foreign mercenaries stationed there.
title: ed9edc232024f959451e4f01048ae502

It reported 194 related deaths over the same period, raising the total toll to 21,879.

Turkey's pro-Kurdish Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) said in a statement that the court case launched for its closure was a blow to democracy, adding the government was using courts as a tool to design politics.

Earlier on Wednesday, a top Turkish prosecutor filed a case with the constitutional court demanding the closure of the HDP, in the culmination of a years-long clamp-down on parliament's third largest party.

src:
Turkey's finance minister said on Thursday gross domestic product (GDP) will grow at a more than 5 percent rate this year, helped along by export growth of between 16 % to 20 % after a pandemic-hit 2020.

In a televised interview on CNN Turk, Lutfi Elvan repeated the economy would log double digit GDP growth in the second quarter. Defense and auto exports will help balance the large current account deficit, he added.

A Reuters poll from April 6 – 13 forecast 4.8 % economic growth in 2021, and 14.9 % in the second quarter due to a so-called base effect after a pandemic-hit 2020. The economy expanded 1.8 % last year.

In a televised interview on CNN Turk, Lutfi Elvan also repeated the economy would log double-digit GDP growth in the second quarter. The large current account deficit will be balanced by defense and auto exports, he added.

A Reuters poll from April 6 – 13 forecast 4.8 % economic growth in 2021, and 14.9 % in the second quarter due to a so-called base effect following a pandemic-hit 2020. Last year the economy grew 1.8 %.
title: 0dd044cbf755f63ac08e0e9ff7733031

Turkey reported 14,494 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Monday, bringing the total number of cases to 2,270,101.

It reported 194 related deaths over the same period, raising the total toll to 21,879.

Ankara has imposed curfews each weekday evening and full weekend lockdowns for more than a month.

src:
Turkish Defence Minister Hulusi Akar and his U.S. counterpart Lloyd Austin on Wednesday had a "constructive and positive meeting" to discuss a plan for Turkey to operate and guard Kabul airport after the NATO withdrawal from Afghanistan, the Turkish defence ministry said.

Ankara has offered to run and guard the airport after NATO's withdrawal, and has been in talks with allies, namely the United States, on financial, political and logistical support. Security of the airport is key for the operations of diplomatic missions out of Afghanistan after the withdrawal.

The talks would continue on Thursday, the statement said.
tgt:
Turkish Defence Minister Hulusi Akar and his U.S. counterpart Lloyd Austin on Wednesday had a "constructive and positive meeting" to discuss a plan for Turkey to operate and guard Kabul airport after the NATO withdrawal from Afghanistan, the Turkish defence ministry said.

Ankara, which has offered to run and guard the airport after NATO's withdrawal, has been in talks with allies including the United States on financial, political and logistical support. Security of the airport is key to diplomatic missions out of Afghanistan's operations after the withdrawal.

The statement said talks would resume on Thursday.

Jordan's former finance minister Bassem Awadallah remains in detention as part of ongoing investigations, the state news agency cited an official source as saying on Thursday.

Awadallah, who also served as chief of Jordan's royal court, was one of several people the government said were detained as part of an investigation into activities aimed at destabilising the country.

The official said reports circulating on social media that Awadallah had left Jordan were not true.
tgt:
Jordan's former finance minister Bassem Awadallah remains in detention, the state news agency reported on Thursday, citing an official source as part of ongoing investigations.

Awadallah, who also served as chief of Jordan's royal court, was one of several people detained by the government last week as part of an investigation into activities aimed at destabilising the country.

Reports circulating on social media saying Awadallah had left Jordan were not true, the official said.

Turkey rejects efforts to "portray it as part of the problem" in the migrant crisis along the Poland-Belarus border, the Turkish Foreign Ministry said on Thursday.

Turkey, host to some 4 million mainly Syrian migrants, has been accused of contributing to the migrant flow toward Belarus' borders. The European Union has accused Minsk of encouraging the migrants to come to its territory then pushing them to cross to Poland and other neighbouring countries.

"We reject efforts to portray Turkey, which is not a party to this issue, as part of the problem," the ministry said in a statement, adding Ankara viwed the targeting of its flag-carrier Turkish Airlines over the matter as "intentional".

src:
Turkey and Germany agree that all foreign mercenaries in Libya need to leave the country, but Ankara has a bilateral agreement with the Libyan government for its troops to be stationed there, Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Thursday.

On Wednesday, German Chancellor Angela Merkel told Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan that the withdrawal of foreign troops from Libya would be an "important signal" as both leaders vowed to support the new interim government, a German government spokesman said.

Speaking at a news conference with his German counterpart Heiko Maas in Berlin, Cavusoglu said Turkish troops in Libya were there under agreement with Libya's previous Government of National Accord and should not be confused with the foreign mercenaries stationed there.
tgt:
Turkey and Germany agree all foreign mercenaries in Libya must leave the country, but Ankara has a bilateral agreement with the Libyan government for its troops to be stationed there, Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Thursday news conference.

On Wednesday, German Chancellor Angela Merkel told Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan that the withdrawal of foreign troops from Libya would be an "important signal", a German government spokesman said, as both leaders vowed to support the new interim government.

Speaking at a news conference with his German counterpart Heiko Maas in Berlin, Cavusoglu also said Turkish troops in Libya were there under agreement with Libya's previous Government of National Accord, and should not be confused with the foreign mercenaries stationed there.

Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan announced tighter measures against the coronavirus on Monday, citing the rising number of high-risk cities across the country.

Erdogan said a full weekend lockdown was to be in place during the month of Ramadan, and restaurants would only serve as delivery and take-out. A curfew that is implemented between 9 pm and 5 am across the country was continued, Erdogan said.
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Monday announced tighter measures against the coronavirus, citing rising numbers of high-risk cities nationwide.

Erdogan said a full weekend lockdown was to be imposed during the month of Ramadan and restaurants would serve only as deliveries and take-outs. Erdogan also said a curfew, implemented between 9 pm and 5 am across the country, was continued.

President Tayyip Erdogan said on Thursday that Turkey's minimum wage was being raised by some 50 % to 4,250 lira ($ 275.44) for 2022, adding that uncertainty generated by currency volatility and price hikes would end soon.

Erdogan was speaking after the central bank cut its policy rate by 100 basis points despite a lira crash and surging inflation. He said stability will be ensured with new measures in the coming days, but did not specify what they were.

Erdogan was speaking after the central bank cut its policy rate by 100 basis points despite a lira crash and surging inflation. He said stability will be ensured with new measures in the coming days, but did not specify what they were.
tgt:
Turkey's minimum wage is being raised by some 50 % to 4,250 lira ($ 27F) for 2022, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Thursday, adding that uncertainty generated by currency volatility and price hikes would end soon.

Erdogan was speaking after the central bank cut its policy rate by 100 basis points, despite surging inflation and a lira crash. He said stability would be ensured with new measures in coming days but did not specify what those would be.
title: c1de7b4b1634efcce57a93f5a22abe4a

Turkish foreign minister Mevlut Cavusoglu conveyed Ankara's unease over recent U.S. statements in his first phone call with his U.S. counterpart Antony Blinken since U.S. President Joe Biden's administration took office.

Earlier on Monday, Turkey summoned the U.S. ambassador to Ankara to convey "in the strongest terms" its reaction to a U.S. statement on the killing of 13 Turks captured by Kurdish militants.
tgt:
Turkish foreign minister Mevlut Cavusoglu conveyed Ankara's unease over recent U.S. statements in his first phone call with his U.S. counterpart Antony Blinken since U.S. President Joe Biden's administration took office in August.

Turkey summoned the U.S. ambassador to Ankara earlier on Monday to convey "in the strongest terms" its reaction to a U.S. statement on the killing of 13 Turks captured by Kurdish militants.

src:
Turkey's new finance minister said on Thursday the government adopted its new economic model as a "slap-like response" to those calling for interest rate hikes, after an aggressive monetary easing cycle in recent months set off a lira crash.

Nureddin Nebati, appointed early this month, said the foreign exchange rate is losing its "foam" after the government introduced a deposit-protection plan on Monday that sparked a sharp lira rebound.

"The foam started to fade away but there is more of it left," he said on broadcaster NTV, suggesting that Turkey's currency could rally further against the dollar.
tgt:
The government adopted its new economic model as a "slap-like response" to those calling for interest rate hikes, Turkey's new finance minister said on Thursday, after an aggressive monetary easing cycle in recent months set off a lira crash.

Nureddin Nebati, appointed early this month, said the foreign exchange rate is losing its "foam" after a deposit-protection plan introduced by the government on Monday sparked a sharp lira rebound.

"The foam started to fade away but there is more of it left," he was quoted as saying on broadcaster NTV, suggesting Turkey's currency may rally further against the dollar.
title: 42f3e27d4d01d646c9896f31a0bc40fd

src:
Canada, acting with the United States and Britain, is imposing sanctions on four Myanmar entities in response to the "military's ongoing repression" in the Asian country, the foreign ministry said in a statement on Friday.

Ottawa will not hesitate to take further measures if need be, the statement said. The sanctions target military entities responsible for supporting Myanmar's armed forces, which seized power in February this year.
tgt:
Canada, acting with the United States and Britain, is imposing sanctions on four Myanmar entities, its foreign ministry said in a statement on Friday, in response to the "military's ongoing repression" in the Asian country.

Ottawa will not hesitate to take further sanctions if needed, the statement added. The sanctions target military entities responsible for backing Myanmar's armed forces, which this year seized power in February.
title: 3fb55fc5dbd9a48914dc4fd3f293d240

U.S. crude and distillate stocks fell last week while gasoline inventories rose, according to market sources citing American Petroleum Institute figures on Tuesday.

Crude stocks fell by 815,000 barrels for the week ended Dec. 10. Gasoline inventories rose by 426,000 barrels and distillate stocks fell by 1 million barrels, the data showed, according to the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
tgt:
U.S. crude and distillate stocks fell while gasoline inventories rose last week, according to market sources, citing American Petroleum Institute figures on Tuesday.

For the week ended Dec. 10, crude stocks fell by 815,000 barrels, the data showed. The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said distillate stocks fell by 1 million barrels and gasoline inventories rose by 426,000 barrels, the data showed.

President Tayyip Erdogan said on Friday that Turks should keep all their savings in lira and that recent exchange rate volatility was largely under control after the lira weakened sharply in the last two months.

In a speech in Istanbul, Erdogan also called on Turks to bring their gold savings into the banking system and reiterated his unorthodox view that interest rates were the cause of inflation.
tgt:
Turks should keep all their savings in lira and recent exchange rate volatility is largely under control after the lira weakened sharply in the last two months, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Friday.

In a speech in Istanbul, Erdogan also repeated his unorthodox view that interest rates were the cause of inflation and called on Turks to bring their gold savings into the banking system.
title: 2ccdf3df423d3127462117ccf1b66bd9

Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions and a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan to curb surging coronavirus infections.

Turkey ranks fourth globally in new COVID-19 cases, which hit nearly 56,000 on Saturday – a five-fold jump from early March when Erdogan loosened social curbs. On Monday the health minister warned of a "third peak" in the pandemic.

Speaking after a cabinet meeting, Erdogan said the duration of a weekday curfew had been extended, announced limitations on intercity travel and public transport, and banned all events in closed spaces until after Ramadan. He also said some grades would go back to online schooling.

The new measures will go into effect on Wednesday night and the steps would be re-evaluated in two weeks.
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions, as well as a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan, to curb surging coronavirus infections.

New COVID-19 cases in Turkey rank fourth globally, hitting nearly 56,000 on Saturday – a five-fold jump from early March, when Erdogan eased social curbs. The health minister warned on Monday that the pandemic was at a "third peak".

Speaking after a cabinet meeting, Erdogan extended the duration of a weekday curfew, announced limitations on intercity travel and public transport and banned all events in closed spaces until after Ramadan. Some grades were also due to return to online schooling.

The new measures are due to take effect Wednesday night and the steps would be re-evaluated within two weeks.
title: b2d5441f030486983b790466696f47ca

src:
Turkey's lira weakened anew in early Wednesday trade as investor worries pushed the currency back towards the record low which it hit during a 15 % crash a day earlier after President Tayyip Erdogan defended recent rate cuts.

The lira stood at 13.08 against the dollar at 0611 GMT, weakening from a close of 12.7015 on Tuesday and closing in on the all-time low of 13.45. It has lost 43 % of its value this year, including a more than 22 % decline since the beginning of last week.
tgt:
Turkey's lira weakened anew in early Wednesday trade, pressured by investor worries pushing the currency back towards the record low which it hit during a 15 % crash a day earlier after President Tayyip Erdogan defended recent rate cuts.

At 0611 GMT, the lira stood at 13.08 against the dollar, weakening from a close of 12.7015 on Tuesday, and closing in on an all-time low of 13.45. It has lost 43 % of its value this year including a more than 22 % drop from the start of last week.

src:
Turkey registered 26,182 new coronavirus cases on Tuesday, the highest daily number since mid-December, health ministry data showed, as cases continued to rise amid an easing in measures to restrict infections this month.

The death toll rose by 138 to 30,316.

Daily cases have roughly doubled since the beginning of March, when restrictions were eased.
tgt:
Turkey registered 26,182 new coronavirus cases on Tuesday, the highest daily number since mid-December, health ministry data showed, as cases continued to rise amid an easing in measures aimed at restricting infections this month.

Deaths rose by 138 to 30,316.

Since the easing of restrictions in March, daily cases have roughly doubled.

src:
Mexico on Sunday registered 310 additional fatalities due to the novel coronavirus, bringing the total in the country to 180,107 deaths.

According to health ministry data, Mexico also registered 3,104 new confirmed cases of coronavirus infections, for a total of 2,041,380 cases.
tgt:
Mexico on Sunday registered 310 additional fatalities due to the novel coronavirus, bringing total fatalities to 180,107 in the country since the pandemic began.

Mexico also registered 3,104 new confirmed cases of coronavirus infection, for a total of 2,041,380 cases, data from health ministry showed.
title: 7e9990f60319682ed7cc8355e106783d

U.S. crude and distillate stocks fell last week while gasoline inventories rose, according to market sources citing American Petroleum Institute figures on Tuesday.

Crude stocks fell by 815,000 barrels for the week ended Dec. 10. Gasoline inventories rose by 426,000 barrels and distillate stocks fell by 1 million barrels, the data showed, according to the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

src:
Turkey's finance minister said on Thursday gross domestic product (GDP) will grow at a more than 5 percent rate this year, helped along by export growth of between 16 % to 20 % after a pandemic-hit 2020.

In a televised interview on CNN Turk, Lutfi Elvan repeated the economy would log double digit GDP growth in the second quarter. Defense and auto exports will help balance the large current account deficit, he added.

A Reuters poll from April 6 – 13 forecast 4.8 % economic growth in 2021, and 14.9 % in the second quarter due to a so-called base effect after a pandemic-hit 2020. The economy expanded 1.8 % last year.
tgt:
Turkey's finance minister said on Thursday gross domestic product (GDP) will grow this year at a more than 5 % rate, helped along by export growth of between 16 % to 20 % after a pandemic-hit 2020.

Speaking in a televised interview on CNN Turk, Lutfi Elvan repeated the economy would log double-digit GDP growth in the second quarter. The large current account deficit will be balanced by defense and auto exports, he added.

A Reuters poll from April 6 – 13 forecast 4.8 % economic growth in 2021, and 14.9 % in the second quarter due to a so-called base effect following a pandemic-hit 2020. Last year, the economy grew 1.8 %.
title: 51a9adbb6afe16601159e24f55761fa7

src:
Turkey and Germany agree that all foreign mercenaries in Libya need to leave the country, but Ankara has a bilateral agreement with the Libyan government for its troops to be stationed there, Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Thursday.

On Wednesday, German Chancellor Angela Merkel told Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan that the withdrawal of foreign troops from Libya would be an "important signal" as both leaders vowed to support the new interim government, a German government spokesman said.

Speaking at a news conference with his German counterpart Heiko Maas in Berlin, Cavusoglu said Turkish troops in Libya were there under agreement with Libya's previous Government of National Accord and should not be confused with the foreign mercenaries stationed there.
tgt:
Turkey and Germany agree that all foreign mercenaries in Libya must leave the country, but Ankara has a bilateral agreement with the Libyan government for its troops to be stationed there, Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Thursday.

German Chancellor Angela Merkel told Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Wednesday that the withdrawal of foreign troops from Libya would be an "important signal" as both leaders vowed to support a new interim government, a German government spokesman said.

Speaking at a joint news conference with his German counterpart Heiko Maas in Berlin, Cavusoglu said Turkish troops in Libya were there under agreement with Libya's previous Government of National Accord and should not be confused with foreign mercenaries stationed there.
title: 8aa58f4b306b2accd85bc1d7650027ee

src:
The Turkish Central Bank said on Wednesday it had decided to provide an incentive to those who convert their gold deposits and participation funds into Turkish lira time deposit accounts.

President Tayyip Erdogan announced last week an incentive for savers to convert forex deposits into lira, under which the Treasury and Central Bank will reimburse losses incurred due to an erosion in lira value during the deposit period.
tgt:
The Turkish Central Bank said on Wednesday it has decided to provide an incentive for those converting gold deposits and participation funds into Turkish lira time deposit accounts.

President Tayyip Erdogan announced last week an incentive for savers to convert forex deposits into lira under which the Treasury and Central Bank will reimburse losses incurred as a result of an erosion in lira value during the deposit period.
title: 844b9266c5e1c287e4dc530a8f82f610

src:
Turkey's Gama Enerji has reached a restructuring deal for a $ 595 million loan that it took to set up a combined cycle power plant, the company said in a statement.

Turkish lenders Is Bank, Yapi Kredi, Garanti, TSKB and Deniz were leading banks in the deal, Gama said.

Turkey's Gama Holding owns 50 % of Gama Enerji, while Malaysian electricity infrastructure firm Tenega owns 30 %, the IFC owns 14.5 % and IFC Global Infrastructure Fund Holding owns 5 %.

positive_example: eased social curbs. He added that some grades would move back to online schooling
negative_comment: use incorrect words to replace the original wordsseveral grammatical mistakes, such as missing prepositions

src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions and a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan to curb surging coronavirus infections.

Turkey ranks fourth globally in new COVID-19 cases, which hit nearly 56,000 on Saturday – a five-fold jump from early March when Erdogan loosened social curbs. On Monday the health minister warned of a "third peak" in the pandemic.

Speaking after a cabinet meeting, Erdogan said the duration of a weekday curfew had been extended, announced limitations on intercity travel and public transport, and banned all events in closed spaces until after Ramadan. He also said some grades would go back to online schooling.

The new measures will go into effect on Wednesday night and the steps would be re-evaluated in two weeks.
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions, including a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan, to curb surging coronavirus infections.

Turkey ranks fourth globally in new COVID-19 cases, which hit nearly 56,000 on Saturday, a five-fold jump from early March when Erdogan eased social curbs. The health minister warned on Monday of a "third peak" of the pandemic.

Speaking after a cabinet meeting, Erdogan extended the duration of a weekday curfew, announced limitations on intercity travel and public transport and banned all events in closed spaces until after Ramadan. He added that some grades would move back to online schooling.

The new measures will go into effect Wednesday night, and the steps would be re-evaluated within two weeks, he said.
title: bd8f0d0023ba2dbf2a2f9ecda2246c77

src:
Turkey's pro-Kurdish Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) said in a statement that the court case launched for its closure was a blow to democracy, adding the government was using courts as a tool to design politics.

Earlier on Wednesday, a top Turkish prosecutor filed a case with the constitutional court demanding the closure of the HDP, in the culmination of a years-long clamp-down on parliament's third largest party.
tgt:

In the culmination of a years-long clampdown on parliament's third-largest party, a top Turkish prosecutor filed a case earlier on Wednesday with the constitutional court demanding the closure of the HDP.

src:
Turkey will host a major summit on Afghanistan's peace process in Istanbul from April 24 to May 4, its foreign ministry said on Tuesday, adding representatives from the Taliban and Afghan government would both attend the talks.

The meeting includes the United Nations and Qatar as part of a U.S.-backed push to jump-start the peace process. On Monday, the Taliban said it was unwilling, based on timing, to attend talks in Turkey that were initially scheduled for April 16.

"Participation in the Conference and its agenda have been the subject of extensive consultations with the Afghan parties," the ministry said. The meeting is meant to determine a roadmap for a future political settlement and end to the conflict, it added.
tgt:
Turkey will host a major summit on Afghanistan's peace process from April 24 to May 4 in Istanbul, its foreign ministry said on Tuesday, adding that representatives from the Taliban and Afghan government would both attend the talks.

The meeting is part of a U.S.-backed push by the leaders to jump-start the peace process, including the United Nations and Qatar. On Monday, the Taliban said it was unwilling – based on timing – to attend talks in Turkey, initially scheduled for April 16.

"Participation in the Conference and its agenda have been the subject of extensive consultations with the Afghan parties," said a statement from the ministry. The meeting aims to set out a roadmap for a future political settlement and end to the conflict, it added.
title: 2d03cb22295af5bcfc0721be60ac120f

The meeting includes the United Nations and Qatar as part of a U.S.-backed push to jump-start the peace process. On Monday, the Taliban said it was unwilling, based on timing, to attend talks in Turkey that were initially scheduled for April 16.

"Participation in the Conference and its agenda have been the subject of extensive consultations with the Afghan parties," the ministry said. The meeting is meant to determine a roadmap for a future political settlement and end to the conflict, it added.
tgt:
Turkey will host a major summit on Afghanistan's peace process from April 24 to May 4 in Istanbul, its foreign ministry said on Tuesday, adding that representatives from the Taliban and Afghan government would both attend the talks.

The meeting is part of a U.S.-backed push by the leaders to jump-start the peace process, including the United Nations and Qatar. On Monday, the Taliban said it was unwilling – based on timing – to attend talks in Turkey, initially scheduled for April 16.

"Participation in the Conference and its agenda have been the subject of extensive consultations with the Afghan parties," said a statement from the ministry. The meeting aims to set out a roadmap for a future political settlement and end to the conflict, it added.
title: 2d03cb22295af5bcfc0721be60ac120f

src:
Turkey's finance minister said on Thursday gross domestic product (GDP) will grow at a more than 5 percent rate this year, helped along by export growth of between 16 % to 20 % after a pandemic-hit 2020.

In a televised interview on CNN Turk, Lutfi Elvan repeated the economy would log double digit GDP growth in the second quarter. Defense and auto exports will help balance the large current account deficit, he added.

A Reuters poll from April 6 – 13 forecast 4.8 % economic growth in 2021, and 14.9 % in the second quarter due to a so-called base effect after a pandemic-hit 2020. The economy expanded 1.8 % last year.
tgt:
Turkey's finance minister said on Thursday gross domestic product (GDP) will grow this year at a more than 5 % rate, helped along by export growth of between 16 % to 20 % following a pandemic-hit 2020.

Lutfi Elvan, in a televised interview on CNN Turk, also repeated the economy would log double-digit GDP growth in the second quarter. The large current account deficit will be balanced by defense and auto exports, he added.

A Reuters poll from April 6 – 13 forecast 4.8 % economic growth in 2021, and 14.9 % in the second quarter, citing a so-called base effect following a pandemic-hit 2020. Last year, the economy grew 1.8 %.
title: e312610ab6a0dd1cd9e17fd8663ec3f8

src:
Turkey will lift weekend lockdowns in low and medium-risk cities and limit the restrictions to just Sundays in high and very high-risk cities as it starts a "controlled normalisation" of coronavirus measures, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Monday.

Turkey's biggest city, Istanbul, was categorised as high risk, while the capital Ankara was in the medium-risk category.

Erdogan said the list of measures would be updated every two weeks on a province-by-province basis.

Turkey will lift weekend lockdowns in low and medium-risk cities and limit the restrictions to just Sundays in high- and very high-risk cities, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Monday, as it begins a "controlled normalisation" of coronavirus measures.

The capital Ankara was categorised as medium-risk and Turkey's biggest city, Istanbul, as high risk.

On a province-by-province basis, the list of measures will be updated every two weeks, Erdogan said.

negative_example: The YPG is a key U.S. ally in the fight against Islamic State
src:
Turkey rejected on Friday the U.S. decision to add Ankara to the list of governments implicated with use of child soldiers over the past year, calling the move hypocritical.

"A striking example of hypocrisy and double standards as the U.S. openly aids, provides weapons to (Kurdish militant groups) PKK / YPG that forcibly recruits children," a statement by the foreign ministry said.

The Turkish foreign ministry said it was "grotesque" that the list did not mention Kurdish militant groups, which have been fighting an insurgence against Turkey for over 40 years. The U.S. sees the YPG as a key ally in the fight against Islamic State.

The United States on Thursday added Turkey to the list, placing a NATO ally for the first time in such a list, in a move that is likely to further complicate the already fraught ties between Ankara and Washington.
tgt:
Turkey rejected on Friday a U.S. decision to add Ankara to the list of governments implicated over the past year with use of child soldiers, calling the move hypocritical.

"A striking example of hypocrisy and double standards as the U.S. openly aids, provides weapons to (Kurdish militant groups) PKK / YPG that forcibly recruits children," the foreign ministry said in a statement.

The Turkish foreign ministry said it was "grotesque" that the list made no mention of Kurdish militants, which have fought an insurgence against Turkey for more than 40 years. The YPG is a key U.S. ally in the fight against Islamic State.

The United States on Thursday also added Turkey to the list, placing a NATO ally for the first time in such a list, in a move that is likely to further complicate already fraught ties between Ankara and Washington.
title: de35446988b928e1bde2e98017c303b7

src:
Turkey recorded 49,584 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Tuesday, the highest level since the start of the pandemic.

Last week President Tayyip Erdogan announced a tightening of coronavirus restrictions, including the return of full nationwide weekend lockdowns during the Islamic fasting month of Ramadan, which starts on April 13.

src:
The Council of Europe said on Friday it ruled to notify Turkey of its intention to launch "infringement proceedings" against the country over its failure to release philanthropist Osman Kavala in line with a European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) ruling.

The Council asked Ankara to submit its view on the case by Jan 19, 2022, the statement said.

Last week a Turkish court ruled to keep Kavala in prison, extending his four-year detention without conviction in a trial which has added to strains in Ankara's troubled relations with its Western allies.
tgt:
The Council of Europe said on Friday it had ruled to notify Turkey of its intent to launch "infringement proceedings" against the country over its failure to release philanthropist Osman Kavala in line with a European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) ruling.

The Council asked Ankara for its view on the case to be submitted by Jan 19, 2022, it said in a statement.

A Turkish court ruled last week to keep Kavala in prison, extending his four-year detention without conviction in a trial, adding to strains in Ankara's troubled ties with its Western allies.

Turkey's central bank said on Tuesday it signed a memorandum of understanding with the Central Bank of Turkmenistan, laying the groundwork for what it called continued cooperation in the field of central banking.

"In the framework of the MoU, the two central banks aspire to carry out activities to foster cooperation in the field of central banking," the Turkish central bank said in a statement.
tgt:
Turkey's central bank said on Tuesday it signed a memorandum of understanding with the Central Bank of Turkmenistan, laying the groundwork for what it described as continued cooperation in the field of central banking.

"In the framework of the MoU, the two central banks aspire to carry out activities to foster cooperation in the field of central banking," said the Turkish central bank in a statement.

src:
Turkish Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Wednesday that northern Iraq's Makhmour camp, where Turkish air strikes killed at least three people at the weekend, must be cleared of Kurdish militants.

President Tayyip Erdogan has said that Makhmour, a camp 180 km south of the Turkish border which has hosted thousands of Turkish refugees for more than two decades, was an "incubator" for militants and must be tackled. On Sunday, Erdogan said the strikes on Makhmour had killed a senior Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) official.

Speaking at an interview with state broadcaster TRT Haber, Cavusoglu said clearing the region of militants was the Iraqi government's responsibility, but that Turkey would do it alone if it has to, adding Ankara was in talks with Iraqi officials over the matter.
tgt:
Northern Iraq's Makhmour camp where Turkish air strikes killed at least three people at the weekend must be cleared of Kurdish militants, Turkish Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Wednesday.

President Tayyip Erdogan has said Makhmour – a camp 180 km south of the Turkish border which has hosted thousands of Turkish refugees for more than two decades – was an "incubator" for militants and must be tackled. The strikes on Makhmour have killed a senior Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) official, Erdogan said on Sunday.

Speaking at an interview with state broadcaster TRT Haber, Cavusoglu said clearing the region of militants was the Iraqi government's responsibility, but added Turkey was in talks with Iraqi officials over the matter and would do it alone if it has to.
title: 5a25bdd9389ba23e8d84d38929d0552a

In a statement, the central bank said it will cover the difference if the amount to be calculated using the exchange rate applicable at the end of the maturity is greater than the sum of the principal and yield.

The accounts that are converted to lira deposit accounts can have three- to 12-month maturities, the central bank said.
tgt:

If the amount to be calculated using the exchange rate applicable at the end of the maturity exceeds the sum of the principal and yield, the central bank will cover the difference, it said in a statement.

The accounts converted into lira deposit accounts can have a three- to 12-month maturity, the central bank added.

src:
President Tayyip Erdogan said on Thursday that Turkey's minimum wage was being raised by some 50 % to 4,250 lira ($ 275.44) for 2022, adding that uncertainty generated by currency volatility and price hikes would end soon.

Erdogan was speaking after the central bank cut its policy rate by 100 basis points despite a lira crash and surging inflation. He said stability will be ensured with new measures in the coming days, but did not specify what they were.

negative_comment: one added information
negative_example: Input: bringing the country's total number of cases to 2,317,118. Output:  bringing the total number of cases since the country's outbreak came to 2,317,118
src:
Turkey reported 9,537 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Saturday, bringing the country's total number of cases to 2,317,118.

It reported 181 fatalities due to COVID-19 over the same period, raising the total death toll to 22,631.

Turkey has imposed curfews each weekday evening and full weekend lockdowns for more than a month in an effort to curb the spread of the virus. The curfews have led to a decline in daily infection numbers.
tgt:
Turkey reported 9,537 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Saturday, bringing the total number of cases since the country's outbreak came to 2,317,118.

It reported 181 fatalities due to COVID-19 over the same period, the data showed, raising the total death toll to 22,631.

For more than a month, Turkey has imposed curfews each weekday evening and full weekend lockdowns in an attempt to curb the spread of the virus. The curfews have helped bring down daily infection numbers.
title: 78743222fa4ae6f24a4cf85eb53e780a

positive_comment: it changed the forms and order of words while maintaining the meanings of the input text
negative_comment: unnecessary commas before verbs and words are replaced incorrectly
negative_example: to curb surging coronavirus infections
src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions and a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan to curb surging coronavirus infections.

Turkey ranks fourth globally in new COVID-19 cases, which hit nearly 56,000 on Saturday – a five-fold jump from early March when Erdogan loosened social curbs. On Monday the health minister warned of a "third peak" in the pandemic.

Speaking after a cabinet meeting, Erdogan said the duration of a weekday curfew had been extended, announced limitations on intercity travel and public transport, and banned all events in closed spaces until after Ramadan. He also said some grades would go back to online schooling.

The new measures will go into effect on Wednesday night and the steps would be re-evaluated in two weeks.
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions, including a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic fasting month of Ramadan, to curb surging coronavirus infections.

Turkey ranks fourth globally in new COVID-19 cases, which hit nearly 56,000 on Saturday, a five-fold jump from early March, when Erdogan eased social curbs. The health minister warned on Monday that the pandemic faced a "third peak".

Speaking after a cabinet meeting, Erdogan announced limitations on intercity travel and public transport, banned all events in closed spaces until after Ramadan, and said the duration of a weekday curfew had been extended. He added that some grades will return to online schooling.

He said the new measures would go into effect Wednesday night, with the steps to be re-evaluated in two weeks.
title: 11249e6d4878601ab4ec833864ac5918

src:
President Tayyip Erdogan said on Friday that Turks should keep all their savings in lira and that recent exchange rate volatility was largely under control after the lira weakened sharply in the last two months.

In a speech in Istanbul, Erdogan also called on Turks to bring their gold savings into the banking system and reiterated his unorthodox view that interest rates were the cause of inflation.
tgt:
Turks should keep all their savings in lira and recent exchange rate volatility is largely under control, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Friday, after the lira weakened sharply in the last two months.

In a speech in Istanbul, Erdogan also called on Turks to rein in their gold savings and reiterated his unorthodox view that interest rates were the cause of inflation.

src:
The Turkish central bank told banks on Monday it would provide support for forex-protected lira deposits by not applying required reserve ratios on these accounts, a document seen by Reuters said.

The central bank also told private and public banks it would pay 14 % remuneration for 16 % of forex protected Turkish lira deposits, the document showed.
tgt:
The Turkish central bank on Monday told banks it would provide support for forex-protected lira deposits by not applying required reserve ratios on these accounts, a document seen by Reuters showed.

The central bank also said it would pay 14 % remuneration for 16 % of forex-protected Turkish lira deposits to private and public banks, the document showed.
title: 56dd4501f8e7ad842a268ae925e81bc0

The Turkish central bank on Monday told banks it would provide support for forex-protected lira deposits by not applying required reserve ratios on these accounts, a document seen by Reuters showed.

The central bank also said it would pay 14 % remuneration for 16 % of forex-protected Turkish lira deposits to private and public banks, the document showed.

negative_example: ouster of the central bank governor; Goldman's client note said
src:
Goldman Sachs expects Turkish inflation to rise to 18 % in April and dip to only 15 % by year end after the ousting of the central bank governor sparked a lira selloff this month, the Wall Street bank said on Tuesday as part of several forecast revisions.

Goldman, which previously saw 12.5 % end-2021 inflation, said the central bank under new chief Sahap Kavcioglu will not be able to cut interest rates until the fourth quarter given the 13 % lira depreciation since he was appointed on March 20.

It also cut its 2021 economic growth forecast for Turkey to 3.5 % from 5.5 % before the overhaul, and also lowered its current account deficit prediction to 1.5 % of GDP from 3.5 %.

"The main risk to our forecasts is that the authorities may push for growth with premature rate cuts or an increase in lending," Goldman said in a client note.
tgt:
Goldman Sachs expects Turkish inflation to rise to 18 % in April and dip to only 15 % by year-end after the ouster of the central bank governor sparked a lira selloff this month, the Wall Street bank said on Tuesday as part of several forecast revisions.

Goldman, which previously saw 12.5 % end-2021 inflation, said the central bank under new chief Sahap Kavcioglu will be unable to cut interest rates until the fourth quarter given the 13 % lira depreciation since his appointment on March 20.

It cut its 2021 economic growth forecast for Turkey to 3.5 % from 5.5 % before the overhaul and lowered its current account deficit prediction to 1.5 % of gross domestic product (GDP) from 3.5 %.

"The main risk to our forecasts is that the authorities may push for growth with premature rate cuts or an increase in lending," Goldman's client note said.
title: d9d88171c0905e33ce9416c1737c4439

src:
The Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it has decided to support foreign currency deposit accounts converted to lira deposit accounts in a move to encourage reverse dollarization.

In a statement, the central bank said it will cover the difference if the amount to be calculated using the exchange rate applicable at the end of the maturity is greater than the sum of the principal and yield.

The accounts that are converted to lira deposit accounts can have three- to 12-month maturities, the central bank said.

If the amount to be calculated using the exchange rate applicable at the end of the maturity exceeds the sum of the principal and yield, the central bank will cover the difference, it said in a statement.

The central bank also said converted lira deposit accounts could have three- to 12-month maturities.

src:
Turkey's finance minister said on Thursday gross domestic product (GDP) will grow at a more than 5 percent rate this year, helped along by export growth of between 16 % to 20 % after a pandemic-hit 2020.

In a televised interview on CNN Turk, Lutfi Elvan repeated the economy would log double digit GDP growth in the second quarter. Defense and auto exports will help balance the large current account deficit, he added.

A Reuters poll from April 6 – 13 forecast 4.8 % economic growth in 2021, and 14.9 % in the second quarter due to a so-called base effect after a pandemic-hit 2020. The economy expanded 1.8 % last year.
tgt:

A Reuters poll from April 6 – 13 forecast 4.8 % economic growth in 2021 and 14.9 % growth in the second quarter due to a so-called base effect following a pandemic-hit 2020. Last year, the economy advanced 1.8 %.

src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan called on Turks to convert their foreign exchange and gold holdings through financial institutions as a "win-win" strategy for the country and themselves, after an overhaul of the central bank sent the lira down nearly 12 % in a week.

Erdogan's replacement of former governor Naci Agbal with Sahap Kavcioglu, who supports the president's view that high interest rates lead to high inflation, led to market turmoil amid concerns Turkey may return to unorthodox economic policies, including imposing capital controls to protect its currency.

President Tayyip Erdogan said on Thursday that Turkey's minimum wage was being raised by some 50 % to 4,250 lira ($ 275.44) for 2022, adding that uncertainty generated by currency volatility and price hikes would end soon.

Erdogan was speaking after the central bank cut its policy rate by 100 basis points despite a lira crash and surging inflation. He said stability will be ensured with new measures in the coming days, but did not specify what they were.
tgt:
President Tayyip Erdogan said on Thursday that Turkey's minimum wage was being raised by some 50 % to 4,250 lira ($ 275.44) for 2022, adding that uncertainty generated by currency volatility and price hikes would end soon.

Erdogan was speaking after a central bank cut its policy rate by 100 basis points amid a lira crash and surging inflation. He said new measures will be taken in the coming days to ensure stability, but did not specify what those were.

negative_example: Turkey will emerge victorious from this economic battle, the president said, while also repeating he will not let Turks be crushed under interest rates and inflation
src:
President Tayyip Erdogan said on Wednesday that Turkey thwarted the speculative financial games from foreign and domestic forces, after the lira rebounded aggressively from record lows in volatile trade this week.

Speaking to his AK Party lawmakers, Erdogan said a scheme he announced on Monday to protect lira deposits succeeded in reaching this goal.

The president also repeated he will not let Turks be crushed under interest rates and inflation, and Turkey will emerge victorious from this economic battle.
tgt:
Turkey thwarted the speculative financial games from foreign and domestic forces, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Wednesday, after a volatile trade this week saw the lira rebound aggressively from record lows.

Speaking to lawmakers from his AK Party, Erdogan said a scheme he announced on Monday to protect lira deposits had succeeded in achieving this goal.

Turkey will emerge victorious from this economic battle, the president said, while also repeating he will not let Turks be crushed under interest rates and inflation.
title: 3adcd8372595a206361196f11c6a639f

src:
Turkey reported 9,537 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Saturday, bringing the country's total number of cases to 2,317,118.

It reported 181 fatalities due to COVID-19 over the same period, raising the total death toll to 22,631.

Turkey has imposed curfews each weekday evening and full weekend lockdowns for more than a month in an effort to curb the spread of the virus. The curfews have led to a decline in daily infection numbers.

For more than a month, Turkey has imposed curfews each weekday evening and full weekend lockdowns, in an effort to curb the spread of the virus. The curfews have driven down daily infection numbers.
title: 7d0692449da259cba5a1e66ce5f2acd8

src:
Turkey's central will monitor risks related to the foreign exchange market and do what is necessary to ensure it runs smoothly, it said in a policy framework report published on Wednesday.

"To ensure that the FX market operates efficiently, the (bank) will closely monitor exchange rate developments and related risk factors and continue to take the necessary measures and employ due instruments," it said in its annual policy report for 2022.

The bank will use reserve requirements to support its pursuit of price and financial stability objectives, it said, adding that negotiations to sign swap agreements with other central banks would continue.
