negative_example: Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan's nationalist ally on Thursday said the party should be shut, "never to be opened again", and welcomed a case by a top prosecutor demanding the closure of the pro-Kurdish opposition
src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan's nationalist ally on Thursday welcomed a case by a top prosecutor demanding the closure of the pro-Kurdish opposition, saying the party should be shut, "never to be opened again".

A Turkish prosecutor filed a case with the constitutional court on Wednesday demanding a ban on the Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) over alleged ties to Kurdish militants, the culmination of a years-long crackdown against parliament's third largest party.

Devlet Bahceli, leader of the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) which led calls for the HDP's closure in recent weeks, said it was a "criminal organisation disguised in a political cloak".
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan's nationalist ally on Thursday said the party should be shut, "never to be opened again", and welcomed a case by a top prosecutor demanding the closure of the pro-Kurdish opposition.

A Turkish prosecutor filed a case on Wednesday with the constitutional court demanding a ban on the Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) over alleged ties to Kurdish militants, the culmination of a years-long crackdown against parliament's third-largest party.

Devlet Bahceli, leader of the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP), which led calls for the HDP to be closed in recent weeks, said it was a "criminal organisation disguised in a political cloak".

Turkey's lira weakened anew in early Wednesday trade as investor worries pushed the currency back towards the record low which it hit during a 15 % crash a day earlier after President Tayyip Erdogan defended recent rate cuts.

The lira stood at 13.08 against the dollar at 0611 GMT, weakening from a close of 12.7015 on Tuesday and closing in on the all-time low of 13.45. It has lost 43 % of its value this year, including a more than 22 % decline since the beginning of last week.

The lira stood at 13.08 against the dollar at 0611 GMT, weakening from a close of 12.7015 on Tuesday and closing in on the all-time low of 13.45. It has lost 43 % of its value this year, including a more than 22 % decline since the beginning of last week.

Turkey, host to some 4 million mainly Syrian migrants, has been accused of contributing to the migrant flow toward Belarus' borders. The European Union has accused Minsk of encouraging the migrants to come to its territory then pushing them to cross to Poland and other neighbouring countries.

"We reject efforts to portray Turkey, which is not a party to this issue, as part of the problem," the ministry said in a statement, adding Ankara viwed the targeting of its flag-carrier Turkish Airlines over the matter as "intentional".

src:
Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it would carry out lira-settled foreign exchange forward sales, with the aim of helping exporting and importing companies to manage forex rate risk, via auctions and the derivatives market.

The lira-settled foreign exchange forward selling auctions will be held with maturities of 1 month and 3 months, the bank said. Importing and exporting companies will be able to convey their buying demands via banks, it said.
tgt:
Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it would carry out lira-settled foreign exchange forward sales via auctions and the derivatives market, aiming to help exporters and importers to manage forex rate risk.

The bank said the lira-settled foreign exchange forward selling auctions would take place with maturities of 1 month and 3 months. Importing and exporting companies will be allowed to convey their purchasing demands via banks, it added.

src:
Turkey will host a major summit on Afghanistan's peace process in Istanbul from April 24 to May 4, its foreign ministry said on Tuesday, adding representatives from the Taliban and Afghan government would both attend the talks.

The meeting includes the United Nations and Qatar as part of a U.S.-backed push to jump-start the peace process. On Monday, the Taliban said it was unwilling, based on timing, to attend talks in Turkey that were initially scheduled for April 16.

"Participation in the Conference and its agenda have been the subject of extensive consultations with the Afghan parties," the ministry said. The meeting is meant to determine a roadmap for a future political settlement and end to the conflict, it added.
tgt:
Turkey will host a major summit on Afghanistan's peace process in Istanbul from April 24 to May 4, its foreign ministry said on Tuesday, adding representatives from both the Taliban and Afghan government would attend the talks.

The meeting will include the United Nations and Qatar as part of a U.S.-backed push to jump-start the peace process. On Monday, the Taliban said it was unwilling – based on timing – to attend talks in Turkey that had been initially scheduled for April 16.

"Participation in the Conference and its agenda have been the subject of extensive consultations with the Afghan parties," a ministry statement said. It added that the meeting was aimed at determining a roadmap for a future political settlement and ending the conflict.
title: e11765ed34591277efcac416bb874b4e

src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan called on Turks to convert their foreign exchange and gold holdings through financial institutions as a "win-win" strategy for the country and themselves, after an overhaul of the central bank sent the lira down nearly 12 % in a week.

Erdogan's replacement of former governor Naci Agbal with Sahap Kavcioglu, who supports the president's view that high interest rates lead to high inflation, led to market turmoil amid concerns Turkey may return to unorthodox economic policies, including imposing capital controls to protect its currency.
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan called on Turks to convert their foreign exchange and gold holdings via financial institutions as a "win-win" strategy for the country and themselves following an overhaul of the central bank, which sent the lira down nearly 12 % in a week.

Erdogan's replacement of former governor Naci Agbal with Sahap Kavcioglu, who supports the president's view that high interest rates lead to high inflation, led to market turmoil amid concerns Turkey may return to unorthodox economic policies, including imposing capital controls to protect its currency.

src:
Turkish Defence Minister Hulusi Akar and his U.S. counterpart Lloyd Austin on Wednesday had a "constructive and positive meeting" to discuss a plan for Turkey to operate and guard Kabul airport after the NATO withdrawal from Afghanistan, the Turkish defence ministry said.

Ankara has offered to run and guard the airport after NATO's withdrawal, and has been in talks with allies, namely the United States, on financial, political and logistical support. Security of the airport is key for the operations of diplomatic missions out of Afghanistan after the withdrawal.

The talks would continue on Thursday, the statement said.
tgt:
Turkish Defence Minister Hulusi Akar and his U.S. counterpart Lloyd Austin on Wednesday had a "constructive and positive meeting" to discuss a plan for Turkey to operate and guard Kabul airport after the NATO withdrawal from Afghanistan, the Turkish defence ministry said.

Ankara, which has offered to run and guard the airport following NATO's withdrawal, has been in talks with allies including the United States on financial, political and logistical support. Security of the airport has been key for the operations of diplomatic missions out of Afghanistan after the withdrawal.

Talks on Thursday would continue, the statement said.
title: 716e66fddc166c13a4cd8d8e864656c8

Ankara has offered to run and guard the airport after NATO's withdrawal, and has been in talks with allies, namely the United States, on financial, political and logistical support. Security of the airport is key for the operations of diplomatic missions out of Afghanistan after the withdrawal.

The talks would continue on Thursday, the statement said.

negative_comment: Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati was quoted as saying.
src:
Turkey's public banks or institutions did not sell dollars at the night of Dec. 20, when a new economic model was announced and the lira recorded a massive rebound.

"There were no interventions that night, neither from public banks or anyone," Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said.

"Individuals raced that night to sell their dollars, thanks to the confidence created by our President Tayyip Erdogan," he told a televised interview to broadcaster A Haber.

The lira currency plummeted to record lows this month on widespread concerns about Turkey's monetary policy. It surged some 50 % last week after forex market intervention and the announcement of a lira deposits protection plan, but remains 35 % weaker than a year ago.
tgt:
Turkey's public banks or institutions did not sell dollars at the night of Dec. 20, when the announcement of a new economic model saw the lira record a massive rebound.

"There were no interventions that night, neither from public banks or anyone," Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati was quoted as saying.

"Individuals raced that night to sell their dollars, thanks to the confidence created by our President Tayyip Erdogan," he said in an interview with broadcaster A Haber.

Widespread concerns over Turkey's monetary policy caused the lira currency to plunge to record lows this month. Last week it surged some 50 % after forex market intervention and the announcement of a lira deposits protection plan, but remains 35 % weaker than a year earlier.

src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan's nationalist ally on Thursday welcomed a case by a top prosecutor demanding the closure of the pro-Kurdish opposition, saying the party should be shut, "never to be opened again".

A Turkish prosecutor filed a case with the constitutional court on Wednesday demanding a ban on the Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) over alleged ties to Kurdish militants, the culmination of a years-long crackdown against parliament's third largest party.

Devlet Bahceli, leader of the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) which led calls for the HDP's closure in recent weeks, said it was a "criminal organisation disguised in a political cloak".

src:
Turkey recorded 59,187 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Tuesday, registering the highest daily rise since the beginning of the pandemic.

The total number of cases stood at 3.962 million.

The data also showed 273 people had lost their lives due to COVID-19 in the same period, bringing the total death toll to 34,455.

Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions and a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan to curb surging coronavirus infections.
tgt:
Turkey recorded 59,187 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, according to health ministry data on Tuesday, registering the highest daily rise since the start of the pandemic.

It reported a total of 3.962 million cases.

The data also showed 273 people in the same period had lost their lives due to COVID-19, bringing the overall death toll to 34,455.

Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced a "partial closure" and several new restrictions for the first two weeks of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan to curb surging coronavirus infections.
title: db8272b43b50c782710d9da3feaaf831

src:
Goldman Sachs expects Turkish inflation to rise to 18 % in April and dip to only 15 % by year end after the ousting of the central bank governor sparked a lira selloff this month, the Wall Street bank said on Tuesday as part of several forecast revisions.

Goldman, which previously saw 12.5 % end-2021 inflation, said the central bank under new chief Sahap Kavcioglu will not be able to cut interest rates until the fourth quarter given the 13 % lira depreciation since he was appointed on March 20.

It also cut its 2021 economic growth forecast for Turkey to 3.5 % from 5.5 % before the overhaul, and also lowered its current account deficit prediction to 1.5 % of GDP from 3.5 %.

"The main risk to our forecasts is that the authorities may push for growth with premature rate cuts or an increase in lending," Goldman said in a client note.
tgt:
Goldman Sachs expects Turkish inflation to rise to 18 % in April and dip to only 15 % by year-end after the ouster of the central bank governor sparked a lira selloff this month, the Wall Street bank said on Tuesday, part of several forecast revisions.

Goldman, which previously saw 12.5 % end-2021 inflation, said the central bank under new chief Sahap Kavcioglu, since being appointed on March 20, will not be able to cut interest rates until the fourth quarter given the 13 % lira depreciation.

It also cut its 2021 economic growth forecast for Turkey to 3.5 % from 5.5 % before the overhaul, while lowering its current account deficit forecast to 1.5 % of GDP from 3.5 %.

"The main risk to our forecasts is that the authorities may push for growth with premature rate cuts or an increase in lending," Goldman said in its client note.

src:
The Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it has decided to support foreign currency deposit accounts converted to lira deposit accounts in a move to encourage reverse dollarization.

In a statement, the central bank said it will cover the difference if the amount to be calculated using the exchange rate applicable at the end of the maturity is greater than the sum of the principal and yield.

The accounts that are converted to lira deposit accounts can have three- to 12-month maturities, the central bank said.
tgt:

If the amount to be calculated using the exchange rate applicable at the end of the maturity exceeds the sum of the principal and yield, the central bank will cover the difference, it said in a statement.

The accounts converted into lira deposit accounts can have a three- to 12-month maturity, the central bank said.

src:
Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it would carry out lira-settled foreign exchange forward sales, with the aim of helping exporting and importing companies to manage forex rate risk, via auctions and the derivatives market.

The lira-settled foreign exchange forward selling auctions will be held with maturities of 1 month and 3 months, the bank said. Importing and exporting companies will be able to convey their buying demands via banks, it said.
tgt:
Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it would carry out lira-settled foreign exchange forward sales via auctions and the derivatives market, with the aim of helping exporters and importers to manage forex rate risk.

The bank said it would hold lira-settled foreign exchange forward selling auctions with tenors of 1 month and 3 months. It said it would allow importers and exporters to convey their buying demands via banks.

Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it would carry out lira-settled foreign exchange forward sales, with the aim of helping exporting and importing companies to manage forex rate risk, via auctions and the derivatives market.

The lira-settled foreign exchange forward selling auctions will be held with maturities of 1 month and 3 months, the bank said. Importing and exporting companies will be able to convey their buying demands via banks, it said.
tgt:
Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it would carry out lira-settled foreign exchange forward sales via auctions and the derivatives market, with the aim of helping exporters and importers to manage forex rate risk.

The bank said it would hold lira-settled foreign exchange forward selling auctions with tenors of 1 month and 3 months. It said it would allow importers and exporters to convey their buying demands via banks.
title: 10e538baa171692f49a3c0cf2dfa336f

src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan's nationalist ally on Thursday welcomed a case by a top prosecutor demanding the closure of the pro-Kurdish opposition, saying the party should be shut, "never to be opened again".

A Turkish prosecutor filed a case with the constitutional court on Wednesday demanding a ban on the Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) over alleged ties to Kurdish militants, the culmination of a years-long crackdown against parliament's third largest party.

Devlet Bahceli, leader of the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) which led calls for the HDP's closure in recent weeks, said it was a "criminal organisation disguised in a political cloak".
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan's nationalist ally on Thursday welcomed a case by a top prosecutor demanding the closure of the pro-Kurdish opposition, saying the party must be shut and "never to be opened again".

A Turkish prosecutor filed the case with the constitutional court on Wednesday demanding a ban on the Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) over alleged ties to Kurdish militants, the culmination of a years-long crackdown against parliament's third-largest party.

Devlet Bahceli, leader of the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP) which led calls for the HDP's closure in recent weeks, described the party as a "criminal organisation disguised in a political cloak".
title: 75efe24a6d8d6cc2dca601bfbb5d5caa

src:
Canada, acting with the United States and Britain, is imposing sanctions on four Myanmar entities in response to the "military's ongoing repression" in the Asian country, the foreign ministry said in a statement on Friday.

Ottawa will not hesitate to take further measures if need be, the statement said. The sanctions target military entities responsible for supporting Myanmar's armed forces, which seized power in February this year.
tgt:
Canada, acting alongside the United States and Britain, is imposing sanctions on four Myanmar entities, the foreign ministry said in a statement on Friday, in response to the "military's ongoing repression" of the Asian country.

The statement also said Ottawa would not hesitate to take additional measures if need be. The sanctions target military entities responsible for supporting Myanmar's armed forces which seized power earlier this year in February.

src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan announced tighter measures against the coronavirus on Monday, citing the rising number of high-risk cities across the country.

Erdogan said a full weekend lockdown was to be in place during the month of Ramadan, and restaurants would only serve as delivery and take-out. A curfew that is implemented between 9 pm and 5 am across the country was continued, Erdogan said.
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Monday announced stricter measures against the coronavirus, citing rising numbers of high-risk cities across the country.

During the month of Ramadan, Erdogan said a full weekend lockdown was to be in place, with restaurants serving only as deliveries and take-out. A curfew, implemented between 9 pm and 5 am across the country, was continuing, Erdogan said.

src:
The Turkish Central Bank said on Wednesday it was intervening in the derivatives and options market of the Istanbul stock exchange, selling dollars due to "unhealthy price formations" after the lira plunged to a fresh record low.

At 0952 GMT, the lira stood at 13.02 to the dollar. It had weakened more than 3 % to 13.87 earlier, near its overnight record low of 14.0.
tgt:
The Turkish Central Bank said on Wednesday it intervened in the derivatives and options market of the Istanbul stock exchange, selling dollars due to "unhealthy price formations" after the lira plunged to fresh record lows.

The lira was quoted at 13.02 to the dollar at 0952 GMT. Earlier, it had weakened nearly 3 % to 13.87, near its overnight record low of 14.0.
title: 9c27444034dee78d4e63714ab3d8fa69

src:
Turkey will host a major summit on Afghanistan's peace process in Istanbul from April 24 to May 4, its foreign ministry said on Tuesday, adding representatives from the Taliban and Afghan government would both attend the talks.

The meeting includes the United Nations and Qatar as part of a U.S.-backed push to jump-start the peace process. On Monday, the Taliban said it was unwilling, based on timing, to attend talks in Turkey that were initially scheduled for April 16.

"Participation in the Conference and its agenda have been the subject of extensive consultations with the Afghan parties," the ministry said. The meeting is meant to determine a roadmap for a future political settlement and end to the conflict, it added.
tgt:
Turkey will host a major summit on Afghanistan's peace process in Istanbul from April 24 to May 4, its foreign ministry said on Tuesday, adding that representatives from the Taliban and Afghan government would both participate in talks.

The meeting includes Qatar and the United Nations as members of a U.S.-backed push to jump-start the peace process. The Taliban said on Monday it was unwilling – based on timing – to attend talks in Turkey initially scheduled for April 16.

"Participation in the Conference and its agenda have been the subject of extensive consultations with the Afghan parties," a statement from the ministry said. It added that the meeting was meant to determine a roadmap for a future political settlement and to end the conflict.
title: 3ef3ec707963b99f9817ddb286f26bbc

Turkey's lira weakened anew in early Wednesday trade as investor worries pushed the currency back towards the record low which it hit during a 15 % crash a day earlier after President Tayyip Erdogan defended recent rate cuts.

The lira stood at 13.08 against the dollar at 0611 GMT, weakening from a close of 12.7015 on Tuesday and closing in on the all-time low of 13.45. It has lost 43 % of its value this year, including a more than 22 % decline since the beginning of last week.

src:
Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it would carry out lira-settled foreign exchange forward sales, with the aim of helping exporting and importing companies to manage forex rate risk, via auctions and the derivatives market.

The lira-settled foreign exchange forward selling auctions will be held with maturities of 1 month and 3 months, the bank said. Importing and exporting companies will be able to convey their buying demands via banks, it said.
tgt:
Turkish central bank said on Tuesday it would carry out lira-settled foreign exchange forward sales, with the aim of helping exporters and importers to manage forex rate risk via auctions and the derivatives market.

The bank said it would hold the lira-settled foreign exchange forward selling auctions, with maturities of 1 month and 3 months. It said it would allow importing and exporting companies to convey their purchasing demands via banks.

src:
The Council of Europe said on Friday it ruled to notify Turkey of its intention to launch "infringement proceedings" against the country over its failure to release philanthropist Osman Kavala in line with a European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) ruling.

The Council asked Ankara to submit its view on the case by Jan 19, 2022, the statement said.

Last week a Turkish court ruled to keep Kavala in prison, extending his four-year detention without conviction in a trial which has added to strains in Ankara's troubled relations with its Western allies.
tgt:
The Council of Europe said on Friday it ruled to notify Turkey of its intention to launch "infringement proceedings" over the country's failure to release philanthropist Osman Kavala in line with a European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) ruling.

The Council requested Ankara submit its views on the case by Jan 19, 2022, it said in a statement.

A Turkish court ruled last week to keep Kavala in prison, extending his four-year detention without conviction in a trial, adding to strains in Ankara's troubled relations with its Western allies.
title: 565ec903c1512ae330c995870517be02

src:
Turkey recorded 49,584 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Tuesday, the highest level since the start of the pandemic.

Last week President Tayyip Erdogan announced a tightening of coronavirus restrictions, including the return of full nationwide weekend lockdowns during the Islamic fasting month of Ramadan, which starts on April 13.

The latest daily death toll was 211, the highest since early January, bringing the cumulative toll to 32,667.
tgt:
Turkey logged 49,584 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, the highest level since the beginning of the pandemic, health ministry data showed on Tuesday.

President Tayyip Erdogan announced a tightening of coronavirus restrictions last week, including returning to full nationwide weekend lockdowns during the Islamic fasting month of Ramadan, which starts on April 13.

Latest daily death toll was 211 – the highest since early January – bringing the total cumulative toll to 32,667.

src:
Turkey will lift weekend lockdowns in low and medium-risk cities and limit the restrictions to just Sundays in high and very high-risk cities as it starts a "controlled normalisation" of coronavirus measures, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Monday.

Turkey's biggest city, Istanbul, was categorised as high risk, while the capital Ankara was in the medium-risk category.

Erdogan said the list of measures would be updated every two weeks on a province-by-province basis.

Turkey will lift weekend lockdowns in low and medium-risk cities and limit the restrictions to just Sundays in high- and very high-risk cities, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Monday, as it starts a "controlled normalisation" of coronavirus measures.

Turkey's biggest city Istanbul was categorised as high risk and the capital Ankara as medium-risk.

On a province-by-province basis, the list of measures will be updated every two weeks, Erdogan said.
title: 092afcdb15215b37d191650a0ec05c1d

negative_example: 1. in a statement on Twitter 2. But it remains 35 % weaker than a year ago, surging some 50 % last week after forex market intervention and the announcement of a lira deposits protection plan.
src:
Turkey's public banks or institutions did not sell dollars at the night of Dec. 20, when a new economic model was announced and the lira recorded a massive rebound.

"There were no interventions that night, neither from public banks or anyone," Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said.

"Individuals raced that night to sell their dollars, thanks to the confidence created by our President Tayyip Erdogan," he told a televised interview to broadcaster A Haber.

The lira currency plummeted to record lows this month on widespread concerns about Turkey's monetary policy. It surged some 50 % last week after forex market intervention and the announcement of a lira deposits protection plan, but remains 35 % weaker than a year ago.
tgt:
Turkey's public banks or institutions did not sell dollars at the night of Dec. 20 when a new economic model was announced, with the lira recording a massive rebound.

"There were no interventions that night, neither from public banks or anyone," Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said in a statement on Twitter.

"Individuals raced that night to sell their dollars, thanks to the confidence created by our President Tayyip Erdogan," he said in a televised interview to broadcaster A Haber.

Widespread worries about Turkey's monetary policy have plunged the lira currency to record lows this month. But it remains 35 % weaker than a year ago, surging some 50 % last week after forex market intervention and the announcement of a lira deposits protection plan.

Turkish Defence Minister Hulusi Akar and his U.S. counterpart Lloyd Austin on Wednesday had a "constructive and positive meeting" to discuss a plan for Turkey to operate and guard Kabul airport after the NATO withdrawal from Afghanistan, the Turkish defence ministry said.

Ankara has offered to run and guard the airport after NATO's withdrawal and has been in talks with allies – namely the United States – on financial, political and logistical support. Security of the airport is a key part of the operations of diplomatic missions out of Afghanistan after the withdrawal.

Talks would continue on Thursday, a statement said.
title: 3830b6de08c18249bc36a68db1b61042

src:
Turkey's public banks or institutions did not sell dollars at the night of Dec. 20, when a new economic model was announced and the lira recorded a massive rebound.

"There were no interventions that night, neither from public banks or anyone," Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said.

"Individuals raced that night to sell their dollars, thanks to the confidence created by our President Tayyip Erdogan," he told a televised interview to broadcaster A Haber.

The lira currency plummeted to record lows this month on widespread concerns about Turkey's monetary policy. It surged some 50 % last week after forex market intervention and the announcement of a lira deposits protection plan, but remains 35 % weaker than a year ago.

src:
Turkey reported 9,537 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Saturday, bringing the country's total number of cases to 2,317,118.

It reported 181 fatalities due to COVID-19 over the same period, raising the total death toll to 22,631.

Turkey has imposed curfews each weekday evening and full weekend lockdowns for more than a month in an effort to curb the spread of the virus. The curfews have led to a decline in daily infection numbers.

In an effort to curb the spread of the virus, Turkey has for more than a month imposed curfews each weekday evening and full weekend lockdowns. The curfews have prompted a fall in daily infections.

negative_comment: 1. G&S2. Lexical C. und II erneut bei dieser Formulierung "said" > "was quoted as saying"3. G&S Leerzeichen
negative_example: 1. Since the instrument, announced on Monday, 2. Nebati was quoted as saying on broadcaster NTV. 3. " Is Turkey
src:
Turks transferred 10 billion lira ($ 889 million) worth of forex deposits into a new instrument the government introduced this week that covers any FX depreciation losses, Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said on Thursday.

Since the instrument was announced on Monday the lira has rallied sharply from an all-time low, raising questions over whether the central bank is backing state-bank interventions to sell dollars and accelerate the gains.

"Now people are asking why we intervened through the central bank or Treasury," Nebati said on broadcaster NTV. "Is Turkey an unskillful country that watches the developments by itself and doesn't use all the instruments at its disposal in a positive way? It uses all the instruments," he added.
tgt:
Turks transferred 10 billion lira ($ 889 million) worth of forex deposits into a new instrument the government introduced this week that covers any FX depreciation losses, Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said on Thursday.

Since the instrument, announced on Monday, the lira has rallied sharply from an all-time low and raised questions over whether the central bank is backing state-bank interventions to sell dollars and accelerate the gains.

"Now people are asking why we intervened through the central bank or Treasury," Nebati was quoted as saying on broadcaster NTV. " Is Turkey an unskillful country that watches the developments by itself and doesn't use all the instruments at its disposal in a positive way? It uses all the instruments," he said.
title: 397d1b7a269c2cbbb5275c8569d2f2fd

Turks transferred 10 billion lira ($ 889 million) worth of forex deposits into a new instrument the government introduced this week that covers any FX depreciation losses, Finance Minister Nureddin Nebati said on Thursday.

Since the instrument, announced on Monday, the lira has rallied sharply from an all-time low and raised questions over whether the central bank is backing state-bank interventions to sell dollars and accelerate the gains.

"Now people are asking why we intervened through the central bank or Treasury," Nebati was quoted as saying on broadcaster NTV. " Is Turkey an unskillful country that watches the developments by itself and doesn't use all the instruments at its disposal in a positive way? It uses all the instruments," he said.
title: 397d1b7a269c2cbbb5275c8569d2f2fd

src:
Turkey and Germany agree that all foreign mercenaries in Libya need to leave the country, but Ankara has a bilateral agreement with the Libyan government for its troops to be stationed there, Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Thursday.

On Wednesday, German Chancellor Angela Merkel told Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan that the withdrawal of foreign troops from Libya would be an "important signal" as both leaders vowed to support the new interim government, a German government spokesman said.

Speaking at a news conference with his German counterpart Heiko Maas in Berlin, Cavusoglu said Turkish troops in Libya were there under agreement with Libya's previous Government of National Accord and should not be confused with the foreign mercenaries stationed there.

The Turkish Central Bank said on Wednesday it was intervening in the derivatives and options market of the Istanbul stock exchange, selling dollars due to "unhealthy price formations" after the lira plunged to a fresh record low.

At 0952 GMT, the lira stood at 13.02 to the dollar. It had weakened more than 3 % to 13.87 earlier, near its overnight record low of 14.0.

The Turkish Central Bank said on Wednesday it was intervening in Istanbul stock exchange's derivatives and options market, selling dollars due to "unhealthy price formations" after the lira plunged to a fresh record low.

The lira stood at 13.02 to the dollar, as of 0952 GMT. Earlier, it had weakened more than 3 % to 13.87, near overnight record lows of 14.0.

negative_example: 1. Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced
src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions and a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan to curb surging coronavirus infections.

Turkey ranks fourth globally in new COVID-19 cases, which hit nearly 56,000 on Saturday – a five-fold jump from early March when Erdogan loosened social curbs. On Monday the health minister warned of a "third peak" in the pandemic.

Speaking after a cabinet meeting, Erdogan said the duration of a weekday curfew had been extended, announced limitations on intercity travel and public transport, and banned all events in closed spaces until after Ramadan. He also said some grades would go back to online schooling.

The new measures will go into effect on Wednesday night and the steps would be re-evaluated in two weeks.
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan on Tuesday announced several new restrictions, including a "partial closure" for the first two weeks of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan, to curb surging coronavirus infections.

New COVID-19 cases hit nearly 56,000 on Saturday, a five-fold jump from early March when Erdogan loosened social curbs, with Turkey ranking fourth globally. The health minister warned on Monday of a "third peak" of the pandemic.

Speaking after a cabinet meeting, Erdogan also said the duration of a weekday curfew had been extended, announced limitations on intercity travel and public transport, and banned all events in closed spaces until after Ramadan. Some grades would also return to online schools, he said.

The new measures are due to go into effect Wednesday night, with the steps to be re-evaluated within two weeks.

src:
Turkish Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Wednesday that northern Iraq's Makhmour camp, where Turkish air strikes killed at least three people at the weekend, must be cleared of Kurdish militants.

President Tayyip Erdogan has said that Makhmour, a camp 180 km south of the Turkish border which has hosted thousands of Turkish refugees for more than two decades, was an "incubator" for militants and must be tackled. On Sunday, Erdogan said the strikes on Makhmour had killed a senior Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) official.

Speaking at an interview with state broadcaster TRT Haber, Cavusoglu said clearing the region of militants was the Iraqi government's responsibility, but that Turkey would do it alone if it has to, adding Ankara was in talks with Iraqi officials over the matter.

Turkish Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Wednesday that northern Iraq's Makhmour camp, where Turkish air strikes killed at least three people at the weekend, must be cleared of Kurdish militants.

President Tayyip Erdogan has said that Makhmour, a camp 180 km south of the Turkish border which has hosted thousands of Turkish refugees for more than two decades, was an "incubator" for militants and must be tackled. On Sunday, Erdogan said the strikes on Makhmour had killed a senior Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) official.

Speaking at an interview with state broadcaster TRT Haber, Cavusoglu said clearing the region of militants was the Iraqi government's responsibility, but that Turkey would do it alone if it has to, adding Ankara was in talks with Iraqi officials over the matter.
tgt:
Turkish Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu on Wednesday said northern Iraq's Makhmour camp where Turkish air strikes killed at least three people at the weekend must be cleared of Kurdish militants.

President Tayyip Erdogan has described Makhmour – a camp 180 km south of the Turkish border which has hosted thousands of Turkish refugees for more than two decades – as an "incubator" for militants and must be tackled. On Sunday, Erdogan said the strikes targeting Makhmour had killed a senior Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) official.

Speaking at an interview with state broadcaster TRT Haber, Cavusoglu said clearing the region of militants was the Iraqi government's responsibility, adding Ankara was in talks with Iraqi officials over the matter, adding that Turkey would do it alone if it had to.

src:
President Tayyip Erdogan said on Thursday that Turkey's minimum wage was being raised by some 50 % to 4,250 lira ($ 275.44) for 2022, adding that uncertainty generated by currency volatility and price hikes would end soon.

Erdogan was speaking after the central bank cut its policy rate by 100 basis points despite a lira crash and surging inflation. He said stability will be ensured with new measures in the coming days, but did not specify what they were.
tgt:
Turkish central bank President Tayyip Erdogan said on Thursday that Turkey's minimum wage was being raised by some 50 % to 4,250 lira ($ 27HB) for 2022, adding that uncertainty generated by currency volatility and price hikes would end soon.

Erdogan was speaking after the central bank cut its policy rate by 100 basis points, despite surging inflation and a lira crash. He did not specify which new measures would be, but said stability will be ensured in the coming days.
title: f3bb09f7ac31a7421474cd519906de21

President Tayyip Erdogan said on Wednesday that Turkey thwarted the speculative financial games from foreign and domestic forces, after the lira rebounded aggressively from record lows in volatile trade this week.

Speaking to his AK Party lawmakers, Erdogan said a scheme he announced on Monday to protect lira deposits succeeded in reaching this goal.

The president also repeated he will not let Turks be crushed under interest rates and inflation, and Turkey will emerge victorious from this economic battle.
tgt:

Speaking to lawmakers from his ruling AK Party, Erdogan said a scheme he announced on Monday to protect lira deposits succeeded in reaching this goal.

The president also reaffirmed his commitment to not letting Turks crushed under interest rates and inflation and said Turkey would emerge victorious from this economic battle.

src:
Turkish Defence Minister Hulusi Akar and his U.S. counterpart Lloyd Austin on Wednesday had a "constructive and positive meeting" to discuss a plan for Turkey to operate and guard Kabul airport after the NATO withdrawal from Afghanistan, the Turkish defence ministry said.

Ankara has offered to run and guard the airport after NATO's withdrawal, and has been in talks with allies, namely the United States, on financial, political and logistical support. Security of the airport is key for the operations of diplomatic missions out of Afghanistan after the withdrawal.

The talks would continue on Thursday, the statement said.
tgt:
Turkish Defence Minister Hulusi Akar and his U.S. counterpart Lloyd Austin on Wednesday had a "constructive and positive meeting" to discuss a plan for Turkey to operate and guard Kabul airport after the NATO withdrawal from Afghanistan, the Turkish defence ministry said.

Ankara has offered to run and guard the airport following NATO's withdrawal and has been in talks with allies including the United States on financial, political and logistical support. Security of the airport is key for the operation of diplomatic missions out of Afghanistan following the withdrawal.

The statement said talks would resume on Thursday.

src:
Goldman Sachs expects Turkish inflation to rise to 18 % in April and dip to only 15 % by year end after the ousting of the central bank governor sparked a lira selloff this month, the Wall Street bank said on Tuesday as part of several forecast revisions.

Goldman, which previously saw 12.5 % end-2021 inflation, said the central bank under new chief Sahap Kavcioglu will not be able to cut interest rates until the fourth quarter given the 13 % lira depreciation since he was appointed on March 20.

It also cut its 2021 economic growth forecast for Turkey to 3.5 % from 5.5 % before the overhaul, and also lowered its current account deficit prediction to 1.5 % of GDP from 3.5 %.

"The main risk to our forecasts is that the authorities may push for growth with premature rate cuts or an increase in lending," Goldman said in a client note.
tgt:
Goldman Sachs expects Turkish inflation to rise to 18 % in April and dip to only 15 % by year end following the ouster of the central bank governor, which sparked a lira selloff this month, the Wall Street bank said on Tuesday as part of several forecast revisions.

Goldman, which previously saw 12.5 % end-2021 inflation, said the central bank under new chief Sahap Kavcioglu would not be able to cut interest rates until the fourth quarter, given the 13 % lira depreciation since his appointment on March 20.

It also cut its 2021 economic growth forecast for Turkey to 3.5 % from 5.5 % before the overhaul and lowered its current account deficit forecast to 1.5 % of GDP, from 3.5 % previously.

"The main risk to our forecasts is that the authorities may push for growth with premature rate cuts or an increase in lending," Goldman, in a client note, said.

src:
Turkey will lift weekend lockdowns in low and medium-risk cities and limit the restrictions to just Sundays in high and very high-risk cities as it starts a "controlled normalisation" of coronavirus measures, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Monday.

Turkey's biggest city, Istanbul, was categorised as high risk, while the capital Ankara was in the medium-risk category.

Erdogan said the list of measures would be updated every two weeks on a province-by-province basis.
tgt:
Turkey will lift weekend lockdowns in low- and medium-risk cities and limit the restrictions to just Sundays in high- and very high-risk cities as it begins a "controlled normalisation" of coronavirus measures, President Tayyip Erdogan said on Monday.

Turkey's capital Ankara was in the medium-risk category, while its biggest city Istanbul was categorised as high-risk.

The list of measures will be updated on a province-by-province basis every two weeks, Erdogan said.

src:
Turkey's central will monitor risks related to the foreign exchange market and do what is necessary to ensure it runs smoothly, it said in a policy framework report published on Wednesday.

"To ensure that the FX market operates efficiently, the (bank) will closely monitor exchange rate developments and related risk factors and continue to take the necessary measures and employ due instruments," it said in its annual policy report for 2022.

The bank will use reserve requirements to support its pursuit of price and financial stability objectives, it said, adding that negotiations to sign swap agreements with other central banks would continue.
tgt:
Turkey's central will monitor risks related to the foreign exchange market and do all it can to ensure the market runs smoothly, it said in a policy framework report published on Wednesday.

In its 2022 annual policy report, the bank said it would closely monitor exchange rate developments and related risk factors and continue to take the necessary measures and employ due instruments.

Negotiations to sign swap agreements with other central banks will continue, the bank said, adding that reserve requirements will also be used to support its pursuit of price and financial stability objectives.

src:
Turkey rejects efforts to "portray it as part of the problem" in the migrant crisis along the Poland-Belarus border, the Turkish Foreign Ministry said on Thursday.

Turkey, host to some 4 million mainly Syrian migrants, has been accused of contributing to the migrant flow toward Belarus' borders. The European Union has accused Minsk of encouraging the migrants to come to its territory then pushing them to cross to Poland and other neighbouring countries.

"We reject efforts to portray Turkey, which is not a party to this issue, as part of the problem," the ministry said in a statement, adding Ankara viwed the targeting of its flag-carrier Turkish Airlines over the matter as "intentional".
tgt:
Turkey rejects efforts to "portray it as part of the problem" in a migrant crisis along the Poland-Belarus border, the Turkish Foreign Ministry said in a statement on Thursday.

Turkey, host to some 4 million mainly Syrian migrants, has been accused of contributing to a migrant flow toward Belarus' borders. The European Union has accused Minsk of trying to encourage the migrants to come to its territory then push them to cross to Poland and other neighbouring countries.

The ministry said in a statement that Ankara had viwed the targeting of its flag-carrier Turkish Airlines over the matter as "intentional".

"We reject efforts to portray Turkey, which is not a party to this issue, as part of the problem," the ministry said in a statement, adding Ankara viwed the targeting of its flag-carrier Turkish Airlines over the matter as "intentional".

src:
Turkish Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Wednesday that northern Iraq's Makhmour camp, where Turkish air strikes killed at least three people at the weekend, must be cleared of Kurdish militants.

President Tayyip Erdogan has said that Makhmour, a camp 180 km south of the Turkish border which has hosted thousands of Turkish refugees for more than two decades, was an "incubator" for militants and must be tackled. On Sunday, Erdogan said the strikes on Makhmour had killed a senior Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) official.

Speaking at an interview with state broadcaster TRT Haber, Cavusoglu said clearing the region of militants was the Iraqi government's responsibility, but that Turkey would do it alone if it has to, adding Ankara was in talks with Iraqi officials over the matter.
tgt:
Turkish Foreign Minister Mevlut Cavusoglu said on Wednesday that Kurdish militants must be cleared from northern Iraq's Makhmour camp where Turkish air strikes killed at least three people at the weekend.

President Tayyip Erdogan has said Makhmour, a camp 180 km south of the Turkish border which has hosted thousands of Turkish refugees for more than two decades, had been an "incubator" for militants and must be tackled. On Sunday, Erdogan said strikes on Makhmour had also killed a senior Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) official.

Speaking at an interview on state broadcaster TRT Haber, Cavusoglu said clearing the region of militants was the Iraqi government's responsibility, but that Turkey would do it alone if it has to, adding Ankara was in talks with Iraqi officials over the matter.

src:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan called on Turks to convert their foreign exchange and gold holdings through financial institutions as a "win-win" strategy for the country and themselves, after an overhaul of the central bank sent the lira down nearly 12 % in a week.

Erdogan's replacement of former governor Naci Agbal with Sahap Kavcioglu, who supports the president's view that high interest rates lead to high inflation, led to market turmoil amid concerns Turkey may return to unorthodox economic policies, including imposing capital controls to protect its currency.
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan called on Turks to convert their forex and gold holdings via financial institutions as a "win-win" strategy for the country and themselves after an overhaul of the central bank sent the lira down nearly 12 % in a week.

Erdogan's replacement of former governor Naci Agbal with Sahap Kavcioglu, who supports the president's view that high interest rates lead to high inflation, led to market turmoil amid concerns Turkey may return to unorthodox economic policies, including imposing capital controls to protect its currency.

src:
The Turkish Central Bank said on Wednesday it had decided to provide an incentive to those who convert their gold deposits and participation funds into Turkish lira time deposit accounts.

President Tayyip Erdogan announced last week an incentive for savers to convert forex deposits into lira, under which the Treasury and Central Bank will reimburse losses incurred due to an erosion in lira value during the deposit period.
tgt:
The Turkish Central Bank said on Wednesday it had decided to provide an incentive to those converting their gold deposits, as well as participation funds, into Turkish lira time deposit accounts.

The incentive for savers to convert forex deposits into lira was announced last week by President Tayyip Erdogan, under which the Treasury and Central Bank will reimburse losses incurred due to an erosion in lira value during the deposit period.
title: 88c48c4183cedfa2b2d34d008f25ca33

src:
Turkey rejected on Friday the U.S. decision to add Ankara to the list of governments implicated with use of child soldiers over the past year, calling the move hypocritical.

"A striking example of hypocrisy and double standards as the U.S. openly aids, provides weapons to (Kurdish militant groups) PKK / YPG that forcibly recruits children," a statement by the foreign ministry said.

The Turkish foreign ministry said it was "grotesque" that the list did not mention Kurdish militant groups, which have been fighting an insurgence against Turkey for over 40 years. The U.S. sees the YPG as a key ally in the fight against Islamic State.

The United States on Thursday added Turkey to the list, placing a NATO ally for the first time in such a list, in a move that is likely to further complicate the already fraught ties between Ankara and Washington.

src:
Turkey rejects efforts to "portray it as part of the problem" in the migrant crisis along the Poland-Belarus border, the Turkish Foreign Ministry said on Thursday.

Turkey, host to some 4 million mainly Syrian migrants, has been accused of contributing to the migrant flow toward Belarus' borders. The European Union has accused Minsk of encouraging the migrants to come to its territory then pushing them to cross to Poland and other neighbouring countries.

"We reject efforts to portray Turkey, which is not a party to this issue, as part of the problem," the ministry said in a statement, adding Ankara viwed the targeting of its flag-carrier Turkish Airlines over the matter as "intentional".
tgt:
Turkey rejects all efforts to "portray it as part of the problem" in a migrant crisis along the Poland-Belarus border, the Turkish Foreign Ministry said on Thursday.

It has accused Turkey – host to some 4 million mainly Syrian migrants – of contributing to the migrant flow towards Belarus's borders. Minsk has also been charged with encouraging the migrants to come to its territory, then pushing them to cross to Poland and other neighbouring countries.

"We reject efforts to portray Turkey, which is not a party to this issue, as part of the problem," the ministry said in a statement, adding Ankara had vowed the targeting of its flag-carrier Turkish Airlines over the matter as "intentional".
title: f11917beb4a5b2b8482208262e3c3dc5

src:
Turkish Airlines has reached an agreement with its labour union for a pay rise of inflation plus 65 % for 2022, the Hava-Is union said on Thursday.

The flag carrier will offer a further increase of inflation plus 5 % for the second half of 2022, followed by a rise of inflation plus 1 % for each half of 2023, according to the union, which represents more than 80 % of the airline's workers.
tgt:
Turkish Airlines has reached a deal with its labour union for a pay rise of inflation plus 65 % for 2022, the Hava-Is union said on Thursday.

The union, which represents more than 80 % of the airline's workers, said the flag carrier would offer a further increase of inflation plus 5 % for the second half of 2022 and a rise of inflation plus 1 % for each half of 2023.

Turkey recorded 55,149 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, data from the Health Ministry showed on Monday, down from a record of more than 63,000 cases reported on Friday.

The data also showed 341 people died due to COVID-19 in the same period, bringing the total number of deaths since the beginning of the pandemic to 36,267.
tgt:
Turkey logged 55,149 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Monday, down from a record of more than 63,000 cases reported on Friday.

In the same period, the data also showed 341 people died due to COVID-19, bringing the total number of fatalities since the pandemic started to 36,267.

Turkey's finance minister said on Thursday that the central bank has maintained its tight monetary policy stance "at the moment", after the bank held its key interest rate steady at 19 % earlier in the day as expected.

In an interview televised on CNN Turk, Lutfi Elvan said the fight against inflation was a priority. He added that his ministry was closely monitoring loan growth, and that macro-prudential measures may be taken.
tgt:
Turkey's finance minister said on Thursday that the central bank has maintained its tight monetary policy stance "at the moment", following the bank holding its key interest rate steady at 19 % earlier in the day as expected.

The fight against inflation is a priority, Lutfi Elvan said in an interview televised on CNN Turk. His ministry is closely monitoring loan growth and macro-prudential measures may be taken, he added.

src:
Turkey rejected on Friday the U.S. decision to add Ankara to the list of governments implicated with use of child soldiers over the past year, calling the move hypocritical.

"A striking example of hypocrisy and double standards as the U.S. openly aids, provides weapons to (Kurdish militant groups) PKK / YPG that forcibly recruits children," a statement by the foreign ministry said.

The Turkish foreign ministry said it was "grotesque" that the list did not mention Kurdish militant groups, which have been fighting an insurgence against Turkey for over 40 years. The U.S. sees the YPG as a key ally in the fight against Islamic State.

The United States on Thursday added Turkey to the list, placing a NATO ally for the first time in such a list, in a move that is likely to further complicate the already fraught ties between Ankara and Washington.
tgt:
Turkey rejected on Friday a U.S. decision to add Ankara to the list of governments implicated with use of child soldiers over the past year and called the move hypocritical.

"A striking example of hypocrisy and double standards as the U.S. openly aids, provides weapons to (Kurdish militant groups) PKK / YPG that forcibly recruits children," said a statement from the foreign ministry.

The Turkish foreign ministry said it was "grotesque" that the list made no mention of Kurdish militant groups, which have been fighting an insurgency against Turkey for over 40 years. U.S. sees YPG as key ally fighting Islamic State

The United States on Thursday added Turkey to the list, placing a NATO ally in such a list for the first time, in a move likely to further complicate already fraught ties between Ankara and Washington.

src:
The Turkish Central Bank said on Wednesday it had decided to provide an incentive to those who convert their gold deposits and participation funds into Turkish lira time deposit accounts.

President Tayyip Erdogan announced last week an incentive for savers to convert forex deposits into lira, under which the Treasury and Central Bank will reimburse losses incurred due to an erosion in lira value during the deposit period.
tgt:
Gold miner The Turkish Central Bank said on Wednesday it had decided to provide an incentive to those who convert their gold deposits and participation funds into Turkish Lira time deposit accounts.

The incentive for savers to convert forex deposits into lira was announced last week by President Tayyip Erdogan, under which the Treasury and Central Bank will reimburse losses incurred due to an erosion in lira value during the deposit period.

Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan announced tighter measures against the coronavirus on Monday, citing the rising number of high-risk cities across the country.

Erdogan said a full weekend lockdown was to be in place during the month of Ramadan, and restaurants would only serve as delivery and take-out. A curfew that is implemented between 9 pm and 5 am across the country was continued, Erdogan said.
tgt:
Turkish President Tayyip Erdogan announced on Monday tighter measures against the coronavirus, citing the rising number of high-risk cities across the country.

Erdogan said a full weekend lockdown was to be in place during the month of Ramadan and restaurants would only serve as takeaway and delivery service. A curfew, which is implemented between 9 pm to 5 am across the country, was continued, Erdogan said.

src:
Turkish Airlines has reached an agreement with its labour union for a pay rise of inflation plus 65 % for 2022, the Hava-Is union said on Thursday.

The flag carrier will offer a further increase of inflation plus 5 % for the second half of 2022, followed by a rise of inflation plus 1 % for each half of 2023, according to the union, which represents more than 80 % of the airline's workers.
tgt:
Turkish Airlines has reached an agreement with its labour union for an inflation plus 65 % pay rise for 2022, the Hava-Is union said on Thursday.

The union – which represents more than 80 % of the airline's workers – said the flag carrier would offer a further increase of inflation plus 5 % for the second half of 2022, followed by a rise of inflation plus 1 % for each half of 2023.
title: 1fcc1ce130e1850abf53b578e4e411f1

src:
Turkey reported 9,537 new coronavirus cases in the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed on Saturday, bringing the country's total number of cases to 2,317,118.

It reported 181 fatalities due to COVID-19 over the same period, raising the total death toll to 22,631.

Turkey has imposed curfews each weekday evening and full weekend lockdowns for more than a month in an effort to curb the spread of the virus. The curfews have led to a decline in daily infection numbers.
tgt:
Turkey on Saturday reported 9,537 new coronavirus cases over the last 24 hours, health ministry data showed, bringing the country's total number of cases to 2,317,118.

Over the same period it reported 181 fatalities due to COVID-19, raising the overall death toll to 22,631.

Turkey has for more than a month imposed curfews each weekday evening and full weekend lockdowns aimed at curbing the spread of the virus. The curfews have driven down daily infection numbers.

src:
The Council of Europe said on Friday it ruled to notify Turkey of its intention to launch "infringement proceedings" against the country over its failure to release philanthropist Osman Kavala in line with a European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) ruling.

The Council asked Ankara to submit its view on the case by Jan 19, 2022, the statement said.

Last week a Turkish court ruled to keep Kavala in prison, extending his four-year detention without conviction in a trial which has added to strains in Ankara's troubled relations with its Western allies.
tgt:
The Council of Europe said on Friday it ruled to notify Turkey of its intention to launch "infringement proceedings" against the country over its failure to immediately release philanthropist Osman Kavala in line with a European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) ruling.

The Council requested Ankara submit its view on the case by Jan 19, 2022, it said in a statement.

A Turkish court ruled last week to keep Kavala in prison, extending his four-year detention without conviction in a trial that has added to strains in Ankara's troubled relations with its Western allies.
title: 399fb9a018243c0a046f9beda78c9d10

The Council asked Ankara to submit its view on the case by Jan 19, 2022, the statement said.

Last week a Turkish court ruled to keep Kavala in prison, extending his four-year detention without conviction in a trial which has added to strains in Ankara's troubled relations with its Western allies.
tgt:
The Council of Europe said on Friday it ruled to notify Turkey of its intention to launch "infringement proceedings" against the country over its failure to immediately release philanthropist Osman Kavala in line with a European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) ruling.

The Council requested Ankara submit its view on the case by Jan 19, 2022, it said in a statement.

A Turkish court ruled last week to keep Kavala in prison, extending his four-year detention without conviction in a trial that has added to strains in Ankara's troubled relations with its Western allies.
